{"title_page": "Arthur Verocai", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n|name                =  Arthur Verocai\n|image               = \n|background          = solo_singer\n|birth_name          = Arthur Verocai\n|birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1945|6|17}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/arthur-verocai-mn0000610730/biography|title=Arthur Verocai Biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_place         = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n|death_date          = \n|death_place         = \n|origin              = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n|Instrument          = Guitar, piano, vocals<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/lectures/arthur-verocai-seriado-serials|title=Arthur Verocai|publisher=[[Red Bull Music Academy]]|year=2006|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|genre               = [[Bossa Nova]], [[Funk]], [[Jazz]], [[Folk-jazz]], [[Latin jazz]]\n|occupation          = Composer, guitarist, record producer\n|years_active        = 1969\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ubiquityrecords.com/artists/ARTHUR-VEROCAI.html|title=Arthur Verocai|publisher=Ubiquity Records|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|label               = Continental, [[Far Out Recordings]], [[Warner Music Group|WEA International]]\n|associated_acts     = [[Azymuth]], [[Ivan Lins]]\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Verocai''' (born June 17, 1945) is a Brazilian composer, singer, and producer.  He released his debut [[Arthur Verocai (album)|self-titled album]] of [[jazz]]-[[samba]] tracks in 1972.  The album was largely ignored in Brazil when it was released, but achieved a cult-status beginning in the 2000s, with some original vinyl copies selling for \u00a32,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundsandcolours.com/articles/brazil/i-threw-everything-away-an-interview-with-arthur-verocai-8776/|title=I THREW EVERYTHING AWAY: AN INTERVIEW WITH ARTHUR VEROCAI|publisher=Sounds And Colors|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he performed his 1972 album with a 30-piece orchestra at [[California State University]]'s Luckman Theater in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thevinylfactory.com/films/arthur-verocai-legend-mr-bongo-reissue/|title=The legend of Arthur Verocai|publisher=[[The Vinyl Factory]]|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://larecord.com/interviews/2009/03/14/arthur-verocai-nothing-to-do-with-tropicalia|title=ARTHUR VEROCAI: NOTHING TO DO WITH TROPICALIA|publisher=[[LA Record]]|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe's been cited as an influence by [[TV on the Radio]], [[Cut Chemist]], [[MF DOOM]] and [[Madlib]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111616420|title=Arthur Verocai: Return Of A Brazilian Secret|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:19em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Arthur Verocai (album)|Arthur Verocai]]''\n|\n*Released: 1972<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/arthur-verocai-mw0000324757|title=Arthur Verocai \u2013 Arthur Verocai|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: Continental\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Saudade Demais''\n|\n*Released: 2002<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicabrasileira.org/arthur-verocai-saudade-demais/|title=Arthur Verocai lan\u00e7a novo disco com participa\u00e7\u00f5es de Criolo e Mano Brown|publisher=M\u00fasica Brasileira|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: Independent release\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Encore''\n|\n*Released: October 15, 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/encore-mw0001182367|title=Arthur Verocai \u2013 Encore|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: [[Far Out Recordings]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''No Voo do Urubu''\n|\n*Released: 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uai.com.br/app/noticia/musica/2016/12/18/noticias-musica,198931/arthur-verocai-lanca-disco-com-participacao-de-criolo-e-mano-brown.shtml|title=Arthur Verocai lan\u00e7a novo disco com participa\u00e7\u00f5es de Criolo e Mano Brown|publisher=UAI|language=Portuguese|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: Selo SESC SP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sescsp.org.br/loja/3802_NO+VOO+DO+URUBU#/content=detalhes-do-produto|title=NO VOO DO URUBU|publisher=Sesc S\u00e3o Paulo|language=Portuguese|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Live albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of live albums, with selected details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:19em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Timeless''\n|\n*Released: March 30, 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/album/arthur-verocai/timeless/|title=Timeless by Arthur Verocai|publisher=Rate Your Music|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Recorded: March 15, 2009\n*Label: Mochilla\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.allmusic.com/artist/arthur-verocai-mn0000610730/biography AllMusic biography]\n* [https://www.ubiquityrecords.com/artists/ARTHUR-VEROCAI.html Arthur Verocai] at Ubiquity Records\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verocai, Arthur}}\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century composers]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Latin music composers]]\n[[Category:M\u00fasica popular brasileira musical groups]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-musician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n|name                =  Arthur Verocai\n|image               = \n|background          = solo_singer\n|birth_name          = Arthur Verocai\n|birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1945|6|17}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/arthur-verocai-mn0000610730/biography|title=Arthur Verocai Biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_place         = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n|death_date          = \n|death_place         = \n|origin              = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n|Instrument          = Guitar, piano, vocals<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/lectures/arthur-verocai-seriado-serials|title=Arthur Verocai|publisher=[[Red Bull Music Academy]]|year=2006|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|genre               = [[Bossa Nova]], [[Funk]], [[Jazz]], [[Folk-jazz]], [[Latin jazz]]\n|occupation          = Composer, guitarist, record producer\n|years_active        = 1969\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ubiquityrecords.com/artists/ARTHUR-VEROCAI.html|title=Arthur Verocai|publisher=Ubiquity Records|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|label               = Continental, [[Far Out Recordings]], [[Warner Music Group|WEA International]]\n|associated_acts     = [[Azymuth]], [[Ivan Lins]]\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Verocai''' (born June 17, 1945) is a Brazilian composer, singer, and producer.  He released a self-titled album of [[jazz]]-[[samba]] tracks in 1972.  The album was largely ignored in Brazil when it was released, but achieved a cult-status beginning in the 2000s, with some original vinyl copies selling for \u00a32,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundsandcolours.com/articles/brazil/i-threw-everything-away-an-interview-with-arthur-verocai-8776/|title=I THREW EVERYTHING AWAY: AN INTERVIEW WITH ARTHUR VEROCAI|publisher=Sounds And Colors|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he performed his 1972 album with a 30-piece orchestra at [[California State University]]'s Luckman Theater in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thevinylfactory.com/films/arthur-verocai-legend-mr-bongo-reissue/|title=The legend of Arthur Verocai|publisher=[[The Vinyl Factory]]|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://larecord.com/interviews/2009/03/14/arthur-verocai-nothing-to-do-with-tropicalia|title=ARTHUR VEROCAI: NOTHING TO DO WITH TROPICALIA|publisher=[[LA Record]]|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe's been cited as an influence by [[TV on the Radio]], [[Cut Chemist]], [[MF DOOM]] and [[Madlib]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111616420|title=Arthur Verocai: Return Of A Brazilian Secret|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:19em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Arthur Verocai (album)|Arthur Verocai]]''\n|\n*Released: 1972<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/arthur-verocai-mw0000324757|title=Arthur Verocai \u2013 Arthur Verocai|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: Continental\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Saudade Demais''\n|\n*Released: 2002<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicabrasileira.org/arthur-verocai-saudade-demais/|title=Arthur Verocai lan\u00e7a novo disco com participa\u00e7\u00f5es de Criolo e Mano Brown|publisher=M\u00fasica Brasileira|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: Independent release\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Encore''\n|\n*Released: October 15, 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/encore-mw0001182367|title=Arthur Verocai \u2013 Encore|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: [[Far Out Recordings]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''No Voo do Urubu''\n|\n*Released: 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uai.com.br/app/noticia/musica/2016/12/18/noticias-musica,198931/arthur-verocai-lanca-disco-com-participacao-de-criolo-e-mano-brown.shtml|title=Arthur Verocai lan\u00e7a novo disco com participa\u00e7\u00f5es de Criolo e Mano Brown|publisher=UAI|language=Portuguese|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n*Label: Selo SESC SP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sescsp.org.br/loja/3802_NO+VOO+DO+URUBU#/content=detalhes-do-produto|title=NO VOO DO URUBU|publisher=Sesc S\u00e3o Paulo|language=Portuguese|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Live albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of live albums, with selected details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:19em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Timeless''\n|\n*Released: March 30, 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/album/arthur-verocai/timeless/|title=Timeless by Arthur Verocai|publisher=Rate Your Music|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Recorded: March 15, 2009\n*Label: Mochilla\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.allmusic.com/artist/arthur-verocai-mn0000610730/biography AllMusic biography]\n* [https://www.ubiquityrecords.com/artists/ARTHUR-VEROCAI.html Arthur Verocai] at Ubiquity Records\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verocai, Arthur}}\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century composers]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Latin music composers]]\n[[Category:M\u00fasica popular brasileira musical groups]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-musician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ecstaticaaron", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Verocai"}
{"title_page": "Solar Entertainment Corporation", "text_new": "{{short description|Filipino Media Company}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Self-published|date=February 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2016}}}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Solar Entertainment Corporation\n| logo = | \n| caption = | \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1976|1|3}} (as a TV movie company)<br>{{start date and age|1988|7|15}} (as a film distribution company)<br>{{start date and age|2000|6|17}} (as a cable television network)<br>{{start date and age|2008|1|1}} (as a broadcast company)\n| type = [[Private company|Private]] ([[Subsidiary]])\n| traded_as = |\n| predecessor = |\n| location_city = '''Master Playout Facility:''' <br> Third Floor, Worldwide Corporate Center, EDSA corner [[Shaw Boulevard]], [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]] <br> '''Corporate Offices:''' <br>Solar Century Tower,\n100 Tordesillas St., Corner H.V. Dela Costa St. Salcedo Village, [[Makati City]]\n| location_country = \n| area_served = Nationwide\n| industry = [[Media (communication)|Media company]]\n| services = Free-to-air TV channels and shows, radio broadcasting, cable television, local and international film distribution, film-making, entertainment, television programs and production, news, sports, websites\n| founder = William Y. Tieng<br>Willy Y. Tieng <!-- In other parts of the country remained under the Tieng management and founder led by former Solar Entertainment Corporation Chairman William Tieng and former Solar Entertainment Corporation Vice Chairman Willy Tieng. However, SEC remained as its licensee until July 2015. -->\n| products = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]], Front Row Channel, [[Solar Sports]], Solar Pictures, Solar Scoop, Sinag Maynila Film Festival\n| key_people = Wilson Y. Tieng <small> ([[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small><br>Gidget Lao <small>(Chief Executive for Business Operations)\n| revenue = [[Philippine Peso|PHP]]1.372 billion <small>([[Fiscal year|FY]] 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\">{{cite web|title=Media Ownnership Monitor Philippines - Solar Entertainment Corporation|url=http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/philippines/owners/companies/detail/company/company/show/solar-entertainment-corporation/|access-date=November 24, 2016|publisher=VERA Files}}</ref>\n| operating_income = PHP124.43 million <small>(FY 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\"/>\n| num_employees = |\n| owner = Solar Films Inc. {{small|(38%)}} <br> Wilson Y. Tieng {{small|(21%)}} <br> William Y. Tieng {{small|(15%)}}\n| subsid = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC Productions]] <br> [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] <br> [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] <br> Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc.\n| homepage = {{URL|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Solar Entertainment Corporation''' (simply known as '''Solar''' or '''SEC''') is a [[Media in the Philippines|Filipino media company]] founded and owned by the siblings of the Tieng family (Wilson, William and Willy Tieng) which also engages in property development, and distribution of imported products and generic pharmaceutical products. <ref> [http://solarresourcesinc.com/about-us/ Solar Resources - About Us] Solarresourcesinc.com, Accessed on 15 December 2015 </ref>\n\nSolar Entertainment operates two [[Free-to-air|digital free-to-air channels]] and two [[cable television|cable channels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/networks|title=List of Solar Networks|website=Solarentertainmentcorp.com}}</ref> Solar also owns a film distribution company (Solar Pictures) and defunct [[freemium]] [[digital television]] service ([[Easy TV (Philippines)|Easy TV Home]]).\n\n==History==\n===Film production and distribution===\nSolar Entertainment was founded and established by the brothers William Tieng, Wilson Tieng and Willy Tieng in 1976.\nSolar Films was then formed in 1988 (one of the first films that distributed by Solar Films is [[Rambo III]] of [[Sylvester Stallone]]), bringing international films (and later, local films since 2009) to the Philippines. Since 2012, Solar has collaborated with independent film director [[Brillante Mendoza]] for a multiple film contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 15, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517114818/http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |archive-date=May 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On March 18, 2015, Solar launched the Sinag Maynila film festival is, which featured five films from a talented group of directors, each with a different vision and approach. The films were shown in select SM Cinemas from March 18 to 24, 2015. The winners were announced at the \u201cGabi ng Parangal\u201d on March 22.\n\n===Cable television===\nOn January 1, 1994, Solar launched on cable television as the Solar Entertainment Channel.\n\nIn 2000, DOMSAT became Solar's subsidiary. As a result, DOMSAT\u2019s teleport is being used by Solar to produce, originate, and distribute its various television program services. Its full service digital broadcast teleport features server technology facility located in Barangay Sta. Cruz, Sumulong Highway, [[Antipolo City]], Rizal. It is built around two encoder platforms, Scientific Atlanta Power Vu Classic(DVB) and Motorola Digicipher II(MPEG-@). Program origination is done on a SeaChange Media Cluster Server System. The facility includes a 500-square-meter studio and various linear and non-linear production bays.<ref name=\"acquisition\">{{cite news|title= MVP-Ang rivalry set to spill over into television with San Miguel acquisition of Solar stake |url= http://www.spin.ph/sports/basketball/news/mvp-ang-rivalry-set-to-spill-over-into-television-with-san-miguel-acquisition-of-solar-stake|date= November 9, 2013|access-date= August 18, 2014}}</ref> Solar Entertainment first launched its namesake entertainment cable channel in the early 2000s, one devoted to American programs. This channel was later known as Solar USA (the acronym stands for \"Ultimate in Suspense and Action\"), and then later simply as USA before it was replaced by two separate channels.\n\nIn January 2004, Solar launched on cable sports alternative channel as Sports Plus.\n\nOn August 23, 2004, Solar Entertainment launched [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] or Entertainment Central, which is positioned as the country\u2019s premier cable female entertainment channel. ETC is a platform that brings its audience closer to their aspirational lifestyle, as embodied by their idols.\n\nOn May 5, 2005, it test launched delivering debuting service. Intended for a predominantly male audience, the company launched the country\u2019s leading general entertainment cable channel, [[Jack TV]], in July.\n\nOn October 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a crime and action cable channel, Crime/Suspense or [[C/S]].\n\nOn December 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a spin-off channel to ETC, [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|ETC 2nd Avenue]], a lifestyle and general entertainment channel. Started as a test broadcast on December 15, 2005, and had its full launch in 2006. The channel was later renamed as 2nd Avenue on January 17, 2007.\n\nOn October 1, 2006, Sports Plus ceased broadcasting and replaced by the [[Basketball TV]] channel formed by Solar, while moving most of Sports Plus programs to [[Solar Sports]].\n\n===As a broadcast company===\nOn January 1, 2008, Solar Entertainment Corporation began to lease block airtime with terrestrial TV networks, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]]. The move was a result of [[SkyCable]] pulling out C/S, ETC, and 2nd Avenue from the cable company's lineup at their own right. Those three started carrying shows from Solar's, with [[C/S]] on RPN, [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]] on SBN, and [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]] on RJTV.\n\n[[File:Solar Sports.png|200px|thumb|left| Former logo of [[Solar Sports]]]]\nOn May 22, 2009, a victory party for [[Manny Pacquiao|Manny \"Pacman\" Pacquiao]], who just became the new IBO (International Boxing Organization) and ''Ring Magazine'' Light Welterweight Champion, was held at the Renaissance Hotel in [[Makati City]], in partnership with [[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network Inc.]] Solar and [[GMA Network|GMA]] executives at that time signed for a partnership in TV coverage of Manny Pacquiao's upcoming boxing matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/photos/1295/gma-victory-party-for-manny-pac-man-pacquiao|title=GMA victory party for Manny 'Pac-Man' Pacquiao|author=|date=|work=PEP.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe C/S cable channel was later rebranded as [[C/S Origin]] in September 2008, while the RPN network later changed its branding to [[C/S 9]] the next month.\n\nOn November 29, 2009, Solar rebranded C/S9 as [[Solar TV]] at 11:00 am with a slogan ''It's A Bright New World'' on RPN. On October 31, 2010, it changed some of its programming content to English/Tagalog with a new slogan ''Kung Saan Lahat Panalo!''.\n\nIn mid-2010, GemCom sold all of its 97% equity share in [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] to Solar for Php 368.8 million. Since then, SBN became a fully owned subsidiary of Solar.\n\nOn February 11, 2011, SEC partnered with [[ABS-CBN|ABS-CBN Corporation]] to air [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) games over free TV starting February 19, 2011. The games are aired on [[Studio 23]] (now ABS-CBN Sports and Action later known as [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action|S+A]]) and [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], but Solar still airs the games daily on [[Basketball TV|BTV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/02/11/11/abs-cbn-air-nba-all-star-free-tv|title=ABS-CBN to air NBA games on free TV|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|date=|work=ABS-CBN.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Solar TV Network logo.png|200px|thumb|left|Logo of Solar TV as a television network]]\nOn March 2, 2011, after SEC acquired 34 percent of RPN's shares from the Philippine government as part of RPN/IBC privatization in 2011, Solar TV finally ventured into news at the end of 2011. On that same day, ETC moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]] while TalkTV launched over [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. TalkTV was formed by then Solar-owned Solar Television Network. The first programs that aired on the channel were ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'', Today's Talk, ''[[NBC Nightly News]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' and ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref name=\"manilastandardtoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011/february/25/vicagustin.isx&d=2011/february/25|title=Tiengs move into news|last=Agustin|first=Victor C.|date=February 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714043823/http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25%2Fvicagustin.isx&d=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25|archivedate=July 14, 2011|access-date=December 10, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/214215/news/nation/coloma-privatization-of-rpn-9-ibc-13-in-the-works Coloma: Privatization of RPN 9, IBC 13 in the works] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News Online]]''. 03-01-2011 Retrieved 03-01-2011{{Clarify|reason=ambiguous date format|date=April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2011, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched [[The Game Channel]] on [[Destiny Cable]]. It conducted its initial test broadcast from April 8, 2011, until September 29. It then began airing on [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM Channel 31]] on August 15, 2011, after BEAM and Solar signed an affiliation deal, which gave the latter the use of the former's facilities. Full broadcast started on September 30, 2011.\n\nIn May 2011, [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] launched the slogan \"Young and Loving It\". It also saw new programs such as the reality series ''[[The Rachel Zoe Project]]'' and ''Bachelor Pad'', drama series ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]'', and ''[[The Secret Circle (TV series)|The Secret Circle]]'', US reality series ''[[The Glee Project]]'', comedy shows like ''[[New Girl]]'' and [[2 Broke Girls]], and local lifestyle show ''[[Etcetera (TV program)|Etcetera]]''. In 2012, ETC includes the reality show ''[[American Idol]]'', local programs like ''[[Project Runway Philippines]]'' (season 3), drama series ''[[The Lying Game (TV series)|The Lying Game]]'', ''[[Emily Owens, M.D.|Emily Owens MD]]'' and ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and local infotainment show ''[[ETC HQ]]''. In 2013, ETC aired comedy-drama series ''[[The Carrie Diaries (TV series)|The Carrie Diaries]]'', sitcom series ''[[Super Fun Night]]'', supernatural drama series ''[[Ravenswood (TV series)|Ravenswood]]'', horror fantasy drama series ''[[The Originals (TV series)|The Originals]]'' and among others.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SolarNews.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Logo as the Solar News and Current Affairs from 2011 until August 22, 2014{{deletable image-caption|date=3 July 2016}}]] -->\n[[Solar News]], known for its back-to-basics and unbiased journalism,{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} was formed in January 2012 during the coverage of the impeachment trial of former Chief Justice Renato Corona. Post-EDSA revolution [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] newsmen Pal Marquez, Jing Magsaysay and [[Pia Hontiveros]] together with former ANC anchors [[Claire Celdran]], [[Mai Rodriguez]] and Nancy Irlanda, known as the pillars of Solar News.{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} Most of its news reporters are from [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] and [[ABS-CBN News Channel|ANC]], as well as from [[NewsWatch (Philippine TV program)|RPN NewsWatch]].<ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/276523/economy/companies/200-rpn-9-employees-to-lose-jobs 200 RPN 9 employees to lose jobs] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News]]''. 10-02-2012 Retrieved 10-02-2012</ref><ref>[http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/10/04/12/ramon-ang-says-talks-buy-solar-entertainment Ramon Ang says in talks to buy Solar Entertainment] ''[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]''. 10-04-2012 Retrieved 10-04-2012</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2011, The Game Channel limited its broadcast on daytime sharing with a new programming service called [[Chase (TV channel)|CHASE]] which takes over the evening block. In February 2012, both services aired a promotion, announcing the split of CHASE and TGC to form themselves as separate channels. On February 15, 2012, The Game Channel finally shuts down on free TV and was relaunched as a cable channel; CHASE was also relaunched as a separate channel, now occupying the entire BEAM broadcast airtime on Free TV.\n\nOn April 3, 2012, Solar transferred its former Salcedo Village facilities to their new facility in Worldwide Corporate Center in [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2012/04/solar-news-update-debuts-new-look.html|title=Solar News Update debuts new look|website=Medianewser.com}}</ref> It also featured a newly constructed set for Solar's then-news division, which would become fully functional three months later.\n\nOn July 16, 2012, Solar News launched its first local newscast ''Solar Network News'', followed by ''Solar Nightly News'', an hourly Solar News Update, Solar Daybreak, and Solar Newsday.\n\nOn September 7, 2012, Jack TV plugged their announcement through CHASE programs bearing the title \"Another Jack TV is rising, coming soon on this channel\" (BEAM Channel 31). This indicated that CHASE was being replaced; finally, on October 20, 2012, Jack City was then launched, marking October 19 as the end of CHASE's broadcasts. [[Jack City]] still does carry some of CHASE's programs however.\n\nIn October 2012, it was found out that Solar News would replace the government-controlled RPN News, as a result of RPN's privatization, making Solar TV covering the entire network's airtime. More than 200 RPN employees, particularly those from the labor union and the NewsWatch staff, were retrenched and RPN News was closed down on October 29, effectively axing NewsWatch and NewsCap. Some retrenched government employees were relocated to either [[People's Television Network|People's Television Network (PTV 4)]] or [[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation|Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation (IBC 13)]] (both State-run broadcasters).\n\n[[File:FvfOmbudsman0222 37.JPG|thumb|left|200px|A [[Toyota HiAce]] van used by Solar News parked at the Office of the Ombudsman.]]\nOn October 30, 2012, at 5:45 am, TalkTV was replaced as Solar News Channel on Channel 21 via [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. The channel saw the relaunch of sports news program ''Solar Sports Desk'' (now known as [[Sports Desk (2004 TV series)|CNN Philippines Sports Desk]]), as well as the initial telecast of the Solar News and Current affairs block in November 2012 comprising five public affairs programs ([[Legal Help Desk|Legal HD]], [[MedTalk]], [[News.PH]], [[Opposing Views]], Elections 2013 and [[News Cafe]]), ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'', ''[[Undercover Boss (U.S. TV series)|Undercover Boss]]'' and the \"Stories\" [[documentary film|documentaries]] block. In January 2013, Solar News Cebuano (now known as [[CNN Philippines Cebuano News]]) made history as the first national newscast delivered in a local dialect. In 2014, it also launched the [[Kapampangan language|Kapampangan]] national newscast, [[Kapampangan News]] and the public service program ''[[Serbisyo All Access]]'', which is shown in [[Filipino language]].\n\nPrior to the channel's transfer to RPN, SNC's flagship newscast (Solar Network News) simulcasted on RPN 9 (free TV only) from the SNC's launch. The news content for RPN (then affiliated with ETC), however, was switched to ''Solar Nightly News'' on January 14, 2013, onwards, to avoid backlash from free TV viewers, particularly Free TV viewers of ''[[American Idol]]'' (in which the original plan was to replace the 6 pm via satellite broadcast to Free TV viewers by Network News, then airs the AI episodes at the 8 pm rerun in simulcast with cable and satellite viewers). Throughout the ''American Idol'' season, as the episodes are repeated at 8 PM on cable, Solar used the separate free TV-only feed, that contains reruns of selected ETC shows (but with advertisements replaced by ETC teasers and promotions) at 8&nbsp;pm and ''Nightly News'' at 9 PM (with additional ETC programs, if necessary) to be used by RPN after each AI via satellite episode before RPN returns to the main ETC feed at 10 PM. This is to retain RPN's news content as it then has no newscast since the axing of NewsWatch.\n\nOn January 3, 2013, SEC launched Blink Cinema (later renamed as [[My Movie Channel]]) with the full broadcast taking effect later that month.\n\nOn April 14, 2013, [[TV5 Network (company)|TV5 Network Inc.]] and Solar Entertainment Corporation joined to broadcast the [[2013 FIBA Asia Championship]] in Manila on Philippine television on August 1\u201311. Aside from [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and its sister channel ([[AksyonTV]]), the games were also broadcast over Solar\u2019s cable channel [[Basketball TV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/interaktv/tv5-solar-team-up-for-2013-fiba-asia-championship-coverage|title=TV5, Solar team up for 2013 FIBA Asia Championship coverage - InterAksyon.com - Sports5|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New management===\nOn May 22, 2013, Solar Entertainment Corporation appointed two officers to manage its broadcasting and cable businesses: Manuel \u201cMeckoy\u201d Quiogue as chief commercial officer and Maria Theresa \u201cMitos\u201d Borromeo as chief operating officer (COO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9news.ph/lifestyle/2013/05/22/solar-entertainment-corp.-appoints-2-new-officers|title=9news.ph - 9news Resources and Information.|author=|date=|work=9news.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, Quiogue suddenly died on May 31, 2013 prior to assuming his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|title=Your life is your message to the world|work=BWorldOnline.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221542/http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|archivedate=September 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn June 28, 2013, [[Jack City]] reduced its free TV broadcast to 18 hours a day on BEAM in compliance with the [[National Telecommunications Commission]]'s guidelines. However, it still continues to air as a cable channel 24 hours a day.\n\nOn November 9, 2013, [[San Miguel Corporation]]'s president and COO, [[Ramon S. Ang|Ramon Ang]], explored the possibility of acquiring a controlling stake in Solar Entertainment Corporation in his personal capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/13606-san-miguel-s-ang-keen-on-solar-tv,-owner-of-rpn-9|title=San Miguel's Ang keen on Solar TV, owner of RPN-9|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/46828/meeting-of-minds-reached-in-talks-with-ramon-ang-for-investment-says-solar-chairman|title='Meeting of minds' reached in talks with Ramon Ang for investment, says Solar chairman|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, no further announcements were made after this and Ang subsequently reached an agreement to acquire a minority stake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|title=EXCLUSIVE - BusinessMirror owner acquires biggest stake in RPN9|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|archivedate=August 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Solar News Channel]] and its partnership moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]] on December 1, 2013, while ETC returned to SBN Channel 21 a day before. (ETC was aired on [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN-21]] from 2008 to 2011 then to RPN-9 from 2011 to 2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.inquirer.net/177231/new-investor-vows-to-turn-rpn-9-around|title=New investor vows to turn RPN 9 around|first=Miguel R. Camus and Doris C.|last=Dumlao|date=|work=Inquirer.net|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> as well as the launch of Solar's video-on-demand website Blink. As a result of the channel swap (on RPN's part), Network News and Nightly News became newscasts on its own right.\n\nIn 2014, Solar Entertainment's Solar One Boracay happened during the Labor Day weekend to showcase its channels (ETC, 2nd Avenue, JackTV, JackCITY, My Movie Channel, The Game Channel, Solar Sports, BTV and NBA Premium TV) through various summer activities all over the island.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164529/http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2014, Solar Entertainment Corporation chief Wilson Tieng announced that he ceded his entire share on [[Solar TV Network]], Inc., including its 34% majority share on RPN, to [[Antonio Cabangon Chua]], owner of business daily [[BusinessMirror]] and [[Aliw Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref>[http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 Exclusive: BusinessMirror owner acquires majority stake in RPN9] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 |date=August 22, 2014 }}, InterAksyon.com, August 20, 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2014/08/21/1360003/cabangon-chua-acquires-rpn-9|title=Cabangon-Chua acquires RPN-9|first=Lawrence|last=Agcaoili|date=August 21, 2014|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Tieng sold Solar TV because they were losing money for operations after purchasing RPN. As a result of this ownership change, STVNI, Solar News Channel and RPN's majority stake were separated from the Tiengs; while ETC, 2nd Avenue, and Jack City reverted to Solar Entertainment's ownership.\n\nOn September 1, 2014, [[Jack City]] ended its run on free TV due to the preparations being made by [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM 31]] for the incoming transition to ISDB-T digital television, though it continues to be broadcast as a separate cable channel. However, Jack City continued to broadcast on cable networks until March 21, 2015. After Jack City's closure to free TV, BEAM aired under blocktime programs from various local production and religious companies. On November 15, 2014, BEAM began being carried on [[SkyCable]] and Destiny Cable subscribers (per compliance with NTC's \"must-carry\" basis). This move resulted of Jack City in a change of its channel assignment for SkyCable and [[Destiny Cable]] subscribers, as well as several pay TV companies.\n\nIn 2015, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched the #1stonPHTV brand of Solar channels for [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]], Jack City and [[My Movie Channel]], with the brand implemented on January 6, 2015. Since then, all SEC channels broadcast first-run foreign television programs with the hashtag #1stonPHTV (First on Philippine TV), which was formerly known as \"Match Airing\" (ETC), \"Playing 1st\" (Jack TV), \"The Newest in the US\" and \"FastCast\" (2nd Avenue) and \"See It First\" (Jack City).\n\n[[The Game Channel]], after almost three years on broadcasting, selling or ceased on February 28, 2015. The channel space was taken over by [[My Movie Channel]] on March 1.\n\nOn March 22, 2015, Jack City was replaced by [[CT (TV channel)|CT]], thus becoming independent from its parent network. Upon launch, the channel broadened its programming focus by adding talk shows, sitcoms and men's lifestyle programs to its roster.\n\nOn March 26, 2015, Solar Entertainment announced its broadcast of the \"Fight Of The Century\" between [[Manny Pacquiao]] and [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] on May 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/sports/2015/03/27/1437964/abs-cbn-gma-tv5-join-hands-air-pacquiao-fight-networks-unite-historic|title=ABS-CBN, GMA, TV5 join hands to air Pacquiao fight: Networks unite for historic broadcast|first=Abac|last=Cordero|date=March 27, 2015|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> As stated in a press conference that day, it was broadcast on May 3 via delayed broadcast in three major television stations in the Philippines, [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]], and [[GMA Network]] (who waived its exclusive contract with Solar to allow its multi-network coverage, but maintained its exclusive live broadcast on its radio division), with [[Solar Sports]] as its main content provider for this historic event in boxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/boxing-mma/pacquiao/88062-pacquiao-mayweather-television-broadcast-ph|title=Pacquiao vs Mayweather to be televised by GMA, ABS-CBN and TV5|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/459458/sports/boxing/pacquiao-mayweather-fight-to-air-live-over-gma-radio-stations-nationwide|title=Pacquiao-Mayweather fight to air live over GMA radio stations nationwide|author=|date=|work=GMANetwork.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2015, My Movie Channel ceased broadcasting. The closure or selling was announced by Solar a day before.\n\n===Rebranding of the four flagship networks===\nOn October 16, 2016, Solar relaunched its flagship channels ETC, 2nd Avenue, Basketball TV and Solar Sports. The four networks unveiled their new logos, on-air graphics and station IDs, which took effect on that day. CT, Jack TV, Shop TV and NBA Premium TV on the other hand remains unchanged. Also that day, Solar launched its corporate campaign slogan ''...There's More To Come'', which evolved in 2017 as ''We go for More''.\n\nIn 2017, Solar Entertainment became the official Philippine broadcaster of the 65th edition of the [[Miss Universe]] in Manila. This led to another deal with [[ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and [[GMA Network|GMA]] (the second time that such deal happened between Solar and the Big 3 networks). According to some sources, a directive from [[Rodrigo Duterte|President Duterte]] ordered that the major networks must cover the prestige pageant as it happens live in the [[Philippines]]. Alongside the Big Three, Solar Entertainment channels [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|etc]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]] and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] aired the pageant simultaneously. It was also in the same year when Solar Entertainment forged a joint venture with the Bermuda-based communications satellite company [[Asia Broadcast Satellite]] to launch the first nationwide free-to-air [[Satellite television#Direct broadcast via satellite|direct-to-home]] satellite television services using the [[C band (IEEE)|C-band]], which is set to launch on the 3rd quarter of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.satellitetoday.com/broadcasting/2017/05/22/abs-solar-group-launch-new-dth-service-philippines/|title=ABS, The Solar Group to Launch New DTH Service in the Philippines|author=Kendall Russell|date=May 22, 2017|work=Satellite Today|access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Carriage disputes==\n===Sky Cable===\n====2008====\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2014}}\nSolar's channels have ceased airing on [[Sky Cable]], the Philippines' largest cable television provider. An insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that these troubles with Sky Cable started when boxer [[Manny Pacquiao]], whose fights Solar Entertainment has the exclusive right to air and distribute to, moved from [[ABS-CBN]], the flagship television network of [[ABS-CBN Corporation]] and the primary owner of [[Sky Cable Corporation]], to rival [[GMA Network]]. Another insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that SkyCable wanted to remove [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] and [[Jack TV]] to make room for their own channels, [[Velvet (TV channel)|Velvet]] (now defunct) and [[Maxxx]] (now defunct). Sky Cable wanted to retain [[C/S]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Solar Sports]] and [[Basketball TV]], but Solar made a decision that they would only renew their contract if Sky Cable carried all six channels. Thus, Solar decided to pull out all their channels rather than remove ETC and Jack TV.\n\nHowever, Solar has signed a deal with local terrestrial channels [[TV5 (Philippines)|ABC]], [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]] for block-time programming. C/S, ETC and 2nd Avenue programming are seen on terrestrial TV channels RPN, SBN and RJTV, respectively, while [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] and [[WWE]] programming were seen on TV5, now moved to RPN (WWE programming are currently being broadcast thru TV5, while its terrestrial NBA coverage were moved to [[ABS-CBN Sports]] under Solar).\n\nMost of its channels were later returned to Sky Cable, while Jack TV would eventually return to its lineup on January 1, 2010 replacing Maxxx.\n\nMeanwhile, Pacquiao's boxing promotion, [[Top Rank]], signed a non-guaranteed contract with [[ABS-CBN Sports]] to exclusively air fights promoted by Top Rank, with the exception of Pacquiao fights which are still signed exclusively through Solar Entertainment.\n\n====2017\u201319====\nOn April 10, 2017, 3 days before the [[2017 NBA Playoffs]] was scheduled to begin (and coincided with the final day of the [[2016\u201317 NBA season|2016\u201317 NBA regular season]]), Basketball TV, [[NBA Premium TV]], Solar Sports, Jack TV and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] (now defunct) were removed by Solar from Sky Cable (including [[Sky Direct]], [[Destiny Cable]] & [[Sky On Demand]] thru video on demand) without any prior announcement from Solar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/basketball/nba/167065-sky-nba-premium-btv-unavailable |title=Sky subscribers frustrated as NBA Premium, BTV unavailable for playoffs start |last= Rola|first=Alyssa |date= April 16, 2017|website=[[Rappler]] |access-date= April 16, 2017|quote=}}</ref> Initially, both Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV were replaced by airing a simulcast of [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action]] with a ticker announcing the unavailability of the channels, with Solar Sports, Jack TV and CT (now defunct) also doing the latter albeit with a black screen. Later, almost all of the pulled-out Solar channels were replaced by an imaging card, initially detailing the unavailability of the channels and then later, announcing that they will discuss with Solar on returning the aforementioned channels; while for BTV and NBA Premium TV, a schedule of the NBA games that will air on [[ABS-CBN]], ABS-CBN Sports and Action and [[Fox Sports Asia|Fox Sports]] within the week and a loop of an NBA promo. Solar did not comment on the situation for the removal of the channels, but sources and some netizens pointed out a carriage dispute between the two parties for not paying an undisclosed price to continue broadcasting these channels, which was later proven true by an article published by the ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]''.\n\nAs the dispute continued, some media enthusiasts and netizens raised concerns of whether these Solar channels will return to Sky and/or Destiny. Others pointed that inaction between the two parties could affect the next long-term local broadcast franchise with the NBA, slated to begin at the Association's 2019-2020 regular season. (Currently, Solar and Sky's parent, ABS-CBN, have a shared broadcast agreement to air the NBA games on pay and terrestrial television, respectively. Rumours circulated that both networks may bid separately, if they could not reach renewal, and use their respective infrastructure to broadcast adequate NBA coverage; otherwise, rival networks with a functioning sports department like [[5 (TV channel)|The 5 Network]] may also seek their own bidding to steal the 2019 contract from both Solar and ABS-CBN.)\n\nNetizens and viewers were dismayed and frustrated by the removal of the said channels by Sky Cable, most notably for BTV and NBA Premium due to the importance of the Playoffs. Some netizens were angered by the removal of the said channels and asked Sky Cable to return the channels before the scheduled Playoffs would begin, however Sky Cable would respond to angered netizens on social media that they are \"fixing the situation with Solar\". Other netizens and viewers would otherwise switch providers from Sky Cable to other cable companies that carried these channels or to other satellite providers like [[Cignal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/news/sky-cable-nba-premium-basketball-tv-negotiations-with-solar |title=SKYcable unable to give timetable for return of NBA Premium, Basketball TV to channel lineup |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=April 15, 2017 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=April 16, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2018, Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV returned to Sky Cable, Sky Direct, & Sky On Demand for the first time in 18 months<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-btv-channels-back-on-skycable-per-advisory-a795-20181016 |title=NBA Premium, BTV channels back on SKYCable, per advisory |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=October 16, 2018 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=October 26, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>; however it was later removed on October 28, 2018 for unknown reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysky.com.ph/MetroManila/updates/1031/2018/10/28/sky-advisory|title=SKY Advisory|website=Me & My SKY: SKY at 25 years}}</ref>\n\nThe carriage dispute officially ended on January 1, 2019 when all Solar channels: Basketball TV, NBA Premium TV, Solar Sports, and Jack TV were restored on Sky Cable (including Sky On Demand & Sky Direct).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-and-btv-are-back-in-skycable-s-channel-lineup-a795-20190101|title=NBA Premium and BTV are back in SKYcable's channel lineup|website=Spin.ph}}</ref>\n\nIronically, [[MTVph]], which is a Solar channel, ended its operations on the same day at that time Sky returned the affected Solar channels. As of 2019, Sky Cable's sister company Destiny Cable still does not carry all the aforementioned Solar channels despite its aforementioned return on Sky Cable.\n\nDuring the aforementioned period, [[Shop TV]], ETC and 2nd Avenue (now defunct) were kept on the air, due to the \"must-carry\" rules by the NTC. MTVph was also kept on the air (until it was discontinued on January 1, 2019) since it was carried in a separate programming agreement outside of the affected channels despite its ownership.\n\n===Dream Satellite TV===\n[[Dream Satellite TV]] ceased carrying three Solar Channels, namely [[Solar Sports]], [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] (which was at that time a cable channel prior to its move to free TV and cable) and [[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]] (now defunct) (except [[C/S 9]]) effective 1 February 2009. Dream's carriage contract with Solar Entertainment, which expired on 31 December 2008 was not renewed by Dream, citing financial constraints as its main reason. The three Solar channels were replaced by A&E's [[History (South East Asian TV channel)|The History Channel]], [[Bio. (South East Asia)|Biography Channel]] and [[Crime & Investigation Network (South East Asia)|Crime and Investigation Channel]]. As of 2017, ETC and 2nd Avenue remained on its lineup due to the \"must-carry\" rules of the NTC. \n\nUnfortunately, Dream Satellite ended its operations on December 31, 2017 due to bankruptcy and its competition with other satellite providers.\n\n==Divisions / Subsidiaries==\n* ETC Productions<!-- ETC Productions is a production arm of the female-oriented TV channel, ETC -->\n* Blink\n* Solar Pictures\n* Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc. (DOMSAT)\n* [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] (acquired in 2010 from Lucio Co's Gem Communications Holdings Corporation)\n* [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] (operator of Solar's digital television service '''Easy TV Home''')\n\n==Filmography of Solar Pictures==\n===Notable local films released or distributed by Solar Pictures===\n* ''Syota ng Bayan'' (2001)\n* ''[[Batas Militar (2006 film)|Batas Militar]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Pacquiao: The Movie]]'' (2006) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''Anak Ng Kumander'' (2007)\n* ''[[Ang Tanging Pamilya: A Marry Go Round|Ang Tanging Pamilya]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Kimmy Dora: Kambal sa Kiyeme]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Wapakman]]'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/cebu-entertainment/483549/8-official-entries-2009-mmff-bared|title=8 official entries to 2009 MMFF bared|author=|date=|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Flames of Love'' (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2012/11/05/863321/flames-love-celebrates-year-faith|title=Flames of Love celebrates the Year of Faith|first=Ricky|last=Lo|date=November 5, 2012|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Sapi'' (2013)\n* ''Mumbai Love'' (2014)\n* ''[[Bonifacio: Ang Unang Pangulo]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Kid Kulafu]]'' (2015) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Ma' Rosa]]'' (2016)\n* ''Mulat'' (2016)\n* ''Apocalypse Child'' (2016)\n* ''[[Ang Larawan]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's Best Picture)\n* ''[[Siargao (film)|Siargao]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's 2nd Best Picture)\n* ''[[Citizen Jake]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Mary, Marry Me]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Rainbow's Sunset]]'' (2018)\n\n==Broadcast assets==\n\n===Terrestrial TV channels===\n* ''[[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]]'' (Cable TV: 2004-present, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2008\u20132011, 2013\u2013present, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2011\u20132013)\n* ''[[Shop TV]]'' (2005\u2013present, digital platform only)\n\n===Cable TV channels===\n* ''Front Row Channel'' (2020-present, joint venture with Jungo TV) \n* ''[[Solar All Access]]'' (2002\u2013present, formerly Solar Sports PPV)\n* ''[[Solar Sports]]'' (1994\u2013present, formerly Solar Entertainment Channel)\n\n===Former subsidiary, divisions and broadcast assets===\n* ''[[Nine Media Corporation]]'' (formerly, Solar Television Network, Inc.; sold to [[Antonio Cabangon-Chua|ALC Group of Companies]])\n** ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (2012\u20132014)\n** ''[[9TV]]'' (2014\u20132015)\n** ''[[Radio Philippines Network]]'' (34%)\n* ''[[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation]]'' (For ''[[NBA]]'', ''[[Shop TV]]'' & ''[[Jai alai|Jai-Alai Games]]'')\n\n===Defunct cable channels and digital TV distribution===\n* ''[[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132018, [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV 29]]: 2008\u20132018, formerly ETC 2nd Avenue)\n* ''[[9TV]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2014\u20132015; owned by [[Nine Media Corporation]])\n* ''[[Aniplus Asia]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Basketball TV|BTV]]'' (2006\u20132019)\n* ''[https://whatson.astro.com.my/channels/boo/251/?cat=movies&lang=multiple-language&stb=404 Boo] (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[C/S Origin]]'' (2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[C/S 9]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132007, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[CT (TV channel)|CT]]'' (2015\u20132017)\n* ''[[Chase (TV channel)|Chase]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Diva Universal (Philippines)|Hallmark Channel/Diva Universal Philippines]]'' (2009\u20132013)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Jack City]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2012\u20132014, Cable TV: 2014\u20132015)\n* ''[[Jack TV]]'' (2005\u20132020)\n* ''[[K-Plus (Southeast Asia)|K-Plus]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Living Asia Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[MTV (Southeast Asia)|MTV]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[MTVph]]'' (2017\u20132018, joint venture with [[Viacom International Media Networks Asia]])\n* ''[[My Movie Channel|Blink Cinema/My Movie Channel]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n* ''[[NBA League Pass]]''\n* ''[[NBA Premium TV]]'' (2010\u20132019)\n* ''[[Outdoor Channel]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Playboy TV]]''\n* ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2013\u20132014, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2012\u20132013)\n* ''Sports Plus'' (2004\u20132006)\n* ''[[Solar TV]]'' ([[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2009\u20132011)\n* ''[[C/S|Solar USA]]'' (2001\u20132005)\n* ''[[Talk TV (Philippines)|Talk TV]]'' ([[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Telenovela Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[The Game Channel|TGC]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012, Cable TV: 2011, 2012\u20132015)\n* ''SciFi/Universal Channel Philippines'' (2009\u20132012)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Zee Sine]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[ZooMoo]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n\n{{small|<sup>1</sup>Joint venture with [[Universal Networks International]]}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n* [http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/owners/companies/ Media Ownership Monitor Philippines - Media Companies: A Duopoly Rules] by VERA Files and [[Reporters Without Borders]]\n\n{{Radio Philippines Network}}\n{{Solar Entertainment}}\n{{Television in the Philippines}}\n{{Philippine cable channels}}\n\n[[Category:Solar Entertainment Corporation| ]]\n[[Category:Media companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippine radio networks]]\n[[Category:Philippine television networks]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Television in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2008]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mandaluyong]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Filipino Media Company}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Self-published|date=February 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2016}}}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Solar Entertainment Corporation\n| logo = | \n| caption = | \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1976|1|3}} (as a TV movie company)<br>{{start date and age|1988|7|15}} (as a film distribution company)<br>{{start date and age|2000|6|17}} (as a cable television network)<br>{{start date and age|2008|1|1}} (as a broadcast company)\n| type = [[Private company|Private]] ([[Subsidiary]])\n| traded_as = |\n| predecessor = |\n| location_city = '''Master Playout Facility:''' <br> Third Floor, Worldwide Corporate Center, EDSA corner [[Shaw Boulevard]], [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]] <br> '''Corporate Offices:''' <br>Solar Century Tower,\n100 Tordesillas St., Corner H.V. Dela Costa St. Salcedo Village, [[Makati City]]\n| location_country = \n| area_served = Nationwide\n| industry = [[Media (communication)|Media company]]\n| services = Free-to-air TV channels and shows, radio broadcasting, cable television, local and international film distribution, film-making, entertainment, television programs and production, news, sports, websites\n| founder = William Y. Tieng<br>Willy Y. Tieng <!-- In other parts of the country remained under the Tieng management and founder led by former Solar Entertainment Corporation Chairman William Tieng and former Solar Entertainment Corporation Vice Chairman Willy Tieng. However, SEC remained as its licensee until July 2015. -->\n| products = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]], [[Jack TV]], [[Solar Sports]], Solar Pictures, Solar Scoop, Sinag Maynila Film Festival\n| key_people = Wilson Y. Tieng <small> ([[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small><br>Gidget Lao <small>(Chief Executive for Business Operations)\n| revenue = [[Philippine Peso|PHP]]1.372 billion <small>([[Fiscal year|FY]] 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\">{{cite web|title=Media Ownnership Monitor Philippines - Solar Entertainment Corporation|url=http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/philippines/owners/companies/detail/company/company/show/solar-entertainment-corporation/|access-date=November 24, 2016|publisher=VERA Files}}</ref>\n| operating_income = PHP124.43 million <small>(FY 2015)</small><ref name=\"financial\"/>\n| num_employees = |\n| owner = Solar Films Inc. {{small|(38%)}} <br> Wilson Y. Tieng {{small|(21%)}} <br> William Y. Tieng {{small|(15%)}}\n| subsid = [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC Productions]] <br> [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] <br> [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] <br> Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc.\n| homepage = {{URL|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Solar Entertainment Corporation''' (simply known as '''Solar''' or '''SEC''') is a [[Media in the Philippines|Filipino media company]] founded and owned by the siblings of the Tieng family (Wilson, William and Willy Tieng) which also engages in property development, and distribution of imported products and generic pharmaceutical products. <ref> [http://solarresourcesinc.com/about-us/ Solar Resources - About Us] Solarresourcesinc.com, Accessed on 15 December 2015 </ref>\n\nSolar Entertainment operates two [[Free-to-air|digital free-to-air channels]] and two [[cable television|cable channels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/networks|title=List of Solar Networks|website=Solarentertainmentcorp.com}}</ref> Solar also owns a film distribution company (Solar Pictures) and defunct [[freemium]] [[digital television]] service ([[Easy TV (Philippines)|Easy TV Home]]).\n\n==History==\n===Film production and distribution===\nSolar Entertainment was founded and established by the brothers William Tieng, Wilson Tieng and Willy Tieng in 1976.\nSolar Films was then formed in 1988 (one of the first films that distributed by Solar Films is [[Rambo III]] of [[Sylvester Stallone]]), bringing international films (and later, local films since 2009) to the Philippines. Since 2012, Solar has collaborated with independent film director [[Brillante Mendoza]] for a multiple film contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 15, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517114818/http://www.solarentertainmentcorp.com/about/page/solar_today |archive-date=May 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On March 18, 2015, Solar launched the Sinag Maynila film festival is, which featured five films from a talented group of directors, each with a different vision and approach. The films were shown in select SM Cinemas from March 18 to 24, 2015. The winners were announced at the \u201cGabi ng Parangal\u201d on March 22.\n\n===Cable television===\nOn January 1, 1994, Solar launched on cable television as the Solar Entertainment Channel.\n\nIn 2000, DOMSAT became Solar's subsidiary. As a result, DOMSAT\u2019s teleport is being used by Solar to produce, originate, and distribute its various television program services. Its full service digital broadcast teleport features server technology facility located in Barangay Sta. Cruz, Sumulong Highway, [[Antipolo City]], Rizal. It is built around two encoder platforms, Scientific Atlanta Power Vu Classic(DVB) and Motorola Digicipher II(MPEG-@). Program origination is done on a SeaChange Media Cluster Server System. The facility includes a 500-square-meter studio and various linear and non-linear production bays.<ref name=\"acquisition\">{{cite news|title= MVP-Ang rivalry set to spill over into television with San Miguel acquisition of Solar stake |url= http://www.spin.ph/sports/basketball/news/mvp-ang-rivalry-set-to-spill-over-into-television-with-san-miguel-acquisition-of-solar-stake|date= November 9, 2013|access-date= August 18, 2014}}</ref> Solar Entertainment first launched its namesake entertainment cable channel in the early 2000s, one devoted to American programs. This channel was later known as Solar USA (the acronym stands for \"Ultimate in Suspense and Action\"), and then later simply as USA before it was replaced by two separate channels.\n\nIn January 2004, Solar launched on cable sports alternative channel as Sports Plus.\n\nOn August 23, 2004, Solar Entertainment launched [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] or Entertainment Central, which is positioned as the country\u2019s premier cable female entertainment channel. ETC is a platform that brings its audience closer to their aspirational lifestyle, as embodied by their idols.\n\nOn May 5, 2005, it test launched delivering debuting service. Intended for a predominantly male audience, the company launched the country\u2019s leading general entertainment cable channel, [[Jack TV]], in July.\n\nOn October 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a crime and action cable channel, Crime/Suspense or [[C/S]].\n\nOn December 15, 2005, Solar Entertainment launched a spin-off channel to ETC, [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|ETC 2nd Avenue]], a lifestyle and general entertainment channel. Started as a test broadcast on December 15, 2005, and had its full launch in 2006. The channel was later renamed as 2nd Avenue on January 17, 2007.\n\nOn October 1, 2006, Sports Plus ceased broadcasting and replaced by the [[Basketball TV]] channel formed by Solar, while moving most of Sports Plus programs to [[Solar Sports]].\n\n===As a broadcast company===\nOn January 1, 2008, Solar Entertainment Corporation began to lease block airtime with terrestrial TV networks, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]]. The move was a result of [[SkyCable]] pulling out C/S, ETC, and 2nd Avenue from the cable company's lineup at their own right. Those three started carrying shows from Solar's, with [[C/S]] on RPN, [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]] on SBN, and [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]] on RJTV.\n\n[[File:Solar Sports.png|200px|thumb|left| Former logo of [[Solar Sports]]]]\nOn May 22, 2009, a victory party for [[Manny Pacquiao|Manny \"Pacman\" Pacquiao]], who just became the new IBO (International Boxing Organization) and ''Ring Magazine'' Light Welterweight Champion, was held at the Renaissance Hotel in [[Makati City]], in partnership with [[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network Inc.]] Solar and [[GMA Network|GMA]] executives at that time signed for a partnership in TV coverage of Manny Pacquiao's upcoming boxing matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/photos/1295/gma-victory-party-for-manny-pac-man-pacquiao|title=GMA victory party for Manny 'Pac-Man' Pacquiao|author=|date=|work=PEP.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe C/S cable channel was later rebranded as [[C/S Origin]] in September 2008, while the RPN network later changed its branding to [[C/S 9]] the next month.\n\nOn November 29, 2009, Solar rebranded C/S9 as [[Solar TV]] at 11:00 am with a slogan ''It's A Bright New World'' on RPN. On October 31, 2010, it changed some of its programming content to English/Tagalog with a new slogan ''Kung Saan Lahat Panalo!''.\n\nIn mid-2010, GemCom sold all of its 97% equity share in [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] to Solar for Php 368.8 million. Since then, SBN became a fully owned subsidiary of Solar.\n\nOn February 11, 2011, SEC partnered with [[ABS-CBN|ABS-CBN Corporation]] to air [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) games over free TV starting February 19, 2011. The games are aired on [[Studio 23]] (now ABS-CBN Sports and Action later known as [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action|S+A]]) and [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], but Solar still airs the games daily on [[Basketball TV|BTV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/02/11/11/abs-cbn-air-nba-all-star-free-tv|title=ABS-CBN to air NBA games on free TV|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|date=|work=ABS-CBN.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Solar TV Network logo.png|200px|thumb|left|Logo of Solar TV as a television network]]\nOn March 2, 2011, after SEC acquired 34 percent of RPN's shares from the Philippine government as part of RPN/IBC privatization in 2011, Solar TV finally ventured into news at the end of 2011. On that same day, ETC moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]] while TalkTV launched over [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. TalkTV was formed by then Solar-owned Solar Television Network. The first programs that aired on the channel were ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'', Today's Talk, ''[[NBC Nightly News]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' and ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref name=\"manilastandardtoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011/february/25/vicagustin.isx&d=2011/february/25|title=Tiengs move into news|last=Agustin|first=Victor C.|date=February 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714043823/http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/insideBusop.htm?f=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25%2Fvicagustin.isx&d=2011%2Ffebruary%2F25|archivedate=July 14, 2011|access-date=December 10, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/214215/news/nation/coloma-privatization-of-rpn-9-ibc-13-in-the-works Coloma: Privatization of RPN 9, IBC 13 in the works] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News Online]]''. 03-01-2011 Retrieved 03-01-2011{{Clarify|reason=ambiguous date format|date=April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2011, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched [[The Game Channel]] on [[Destiny Cable]]. It conducted its initial test broadcast from April 8, 2011, until September 29. It then began airing on [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM Channel 31]] on August 15, 2011, after BEAM and Solar signed an affiliation deal, which gave the latter the use of the former's facilities. Full broadcast started on September 30, 2011.\n\nIn May 2011, [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] launched the slogan \"Young and Loving It\". It also saw new programs such as the reality series ''[[The Rachel Zoe Project]]'' and ''Bachelor Pad'', drama series ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]'', and ''[[The Secret Circle (TV series)|The Secret Circle]]'', US reality series ''[[The Glee Project]]'', comedy shows like ''[[New Girl]]'' and [[2 Broke Girls]], and local lifestyle show ''[[Etcetera (TV program)|Etcetera]]''. In 2012, ETC includes the reality show ''[[American Idol]]'', local programs like ''[[Project Runway Philippines]]'' (season 3), drama series ''[[The Lying Game (TV series)|The Lying Game]]'', ''[[Emily Owens, M.D.|Emily Owens MD]]'' and ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and local infotainment show ''[[ETC HQ]]''. In 2013, ETC aired comedy-drama series ''[[The Carrie Diaries (TV series)|The Carrie Diaries]]'', sitcom series ''[[Super Fun Night]]'', supernatural drama series ''[[Ravenswood (TV series)|Ravenswood]]'', horror fantasy drama series ''[[The Originals (TV series)|The Originals]]'' and among others.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SolarNews.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Logo as the Solar News and Current Affairs from 2011 until August 22, 2014{{deletable image-caption|date=3 July 2016}}]] -->\n[[Solar News]], known for its back-to-basics and unbiased journalism,{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} was formed in January 2012 during the coverage of the impeachment trial of former Chief Justice Renato Corona. Post-EDSA revolution [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] newsmen Pal Marquez, Jing Magsaysay and [[Pia Hontiveros]] together with former ANC anchors [[Claire Celdran]], [[Mai Rodriguez]] and Nancy Irlanda, known as the pillars of Solar News.{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} Most of its news reporters are from [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] and [[ABS-CBN News Channel|ANC]], as well as from [[NewsWatch (Philippine TV program)|RPN NewsWatch]].<ref>[http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/276523/economy/companies/200-rpn-9-employees-to-lose-jobs 200 RPN 9 employees to lose jobs] ''[[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMA News]]''. 10-02-2012 Retrieved 10-02-2012</ref><ref>[http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/10/04/12/ramon-ang-says-talks-buy-solar-entertainment Ramon Ang says in talks to buy Solar Entertainment] ''[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]''. 10-04-2012 Retrieved 10-04-2012</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2011, The Game Channel limited its broadcast on daytime sharing with a new programming service called [[Chase (TV channel)|CHASE]] which takes over the evening block. In February 2012, both services aired a promotion, announcing the split of CHASE and TGC to form themselves as separate channels. On February 15, 2012, The Game Channel finally shuts down on free TV and was relaunched as a cable channel; CHASE was also relaunched as a separate channel, now occupying the entire BEAM broadcast airtime on Free TV.\n\nOn April 3, 2012, Solar transferred its former Salcedo Village facilities to their new facility in Worldwide Corporate Center in [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medianewser.com/2012/04/solar-news-update-debuts-new-look.html|title=Solar News Update debuts new look|website=Medianewser.com}}</ref> It also featured a newly constructed set for Solar's then-news division, which would become fully functional three months later.\n\nOn July 16, 2012, Solar News launched its first local newscast ''Solar Network News'', followed by ''Solar Nightly News'', an hourly Solar News Update, Solar Daybreak, and Solar Newsday.\n\nOn September 7, 2012, Jack TV plugged their announcement through CHASE programs bearing the title \"Another Jack TV is rising, coming soon on this channel\" (BEAM Channel 31). This indicated that CHASE was being replaced; finally, on October 20, 2012, Jack City was then launched, marking October 19 as the end of CHASE's broadcasts. [[Jack City]] still does carry some of CHASE's programs however.\n\nIn October 2012, it was found out that Solar News would replace the government-controlled RPN News, as a result of RPN's privatization, making Solar TV covering the entire network's airtime. More than 200 RPN employees, particularly those from the labor union and the NewsWatch staff, were retrenched and RPN News was closed down on October 29, effectively axing NewsWatch and NewsCap. Some retrenched government employees were relocated to either [[People's Television Network|People's Television Network (PTV 4)]] or [[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation|Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation (IBC 13)]] (both State-run broadcasters).\n\n[[File:FvfOmbudsman0222 37.JPG|thumb|left|200px|A [[Toyota HiAce]] van used by Solar News parked at the Office of the Ombudsman.]]\nOn October 30, 2012, at 5:45 am, TalkTV was replaced as Solar News Channel on Channel 21 via [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]]. The channel saw the relaunch of sports news program ''Solar Sports Desk'' (now known as [[Sports Desk (2004 TV series)|CNN Philippines Sports Desk]]), as well as the initial telecast of the Solar News and Current affairs block in November 2012 comprising five public affairs programs ([[Legal Help Desk|Legal HD]], [[MedTalk]], [[News.PH]], [[Opposing Views]], Elections 2013 and [[News Cafe]]), ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'', ''[[Undercover Boss (U.S. TV series)|Undercover Boss]]'' and the \"Stories\" [[documentary film|documentaries]] block. In January 2013, Solar News Cebuano (now known as [[CNN Philippines Cebuano News]]) made history as the first national newscast delivered in a local dialect. In 2014, it also launched the [[Kapampangan language|Kapampangan]] national newscast, [[Kapampangan News]] and the public service program ''[[Serbisyo All Access]]'', which is shown in [[Filipino language]].\n\nPrior to the channel's transfer to RPN, SNC's flagship newscast (Solar Network News) simulcasted on RPN 9 (free TV only) from the SNC's launch. The news content for RPN (then affiliated with ETC), however, was switched to ''Solar Nightly News'' on January 14, 2013, onwards, to avoid backlash from free TV viewers, particularly Free TV viewers of ''[[American Idol]]'' (in which the original plan was to replace the 6 pm via satellite broadcast to Free TV viewers by Network News, then airs the AI episodes at the 8 pm rerun in simulcast with cable and satellite viewers). Throughout the ''American Idol'' season, as the episodes are repeated at 8 PM on cable, Solar used the separate free TV-only feed, that contains reruns of selected ETC shows (but with advertisements replaced by ETC teasers and promotions) at 8&nbsp;pm and ''Nightly News'' at 9 PM (with additional ETC programs, if necessary) to be used by RPN after each AI via satellite episode before RPN returns to the main ETC feed at 10 PM. This is to retain RPN's news content as it then has no newscast since the axing of NewsWatch.\n\nOn January 3, 2013, SEC launched Blink Cinema (later renamed as [[My Movie Channel]]) with the full broadcast taking effect later that month.\n\nOn April 14, 2013, [[TV5 Network (company)|TV5 Network Inc.]] and Solar Entertainment Corporation joined to broadcast the [[2013 FIBA Asia Championship]] in Manila on Philippine television on August 1\u201311. Aside from [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and its sister channel ([[AksyonTV]]), the games were also broadcast over Solar\u2019s cable channel [[Basketball TV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/interaktv/tv5-solar-team-up-for-2013-fiba-asia-championship-coverage|title=TV5, Solar team up for 2013 FIBA Asia Championship coverage - InterAksyon.com - Sports5|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New management===\nOn May 22, 2013, Solar Entertainment Corporation appointed two officers to manage its broadcasting and cable businesses: Manuel \u201cMeckoy\u201d Quiogue as chief commercial officer and Maria Theresa \u201cMitos\u201d Borromeo as chief operating officer (COO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9news.ph/lifestyle/2013/05/22/solar-entertainment-corp.-appoints-2-new-officers|title=9news.ph - 9news Resources and Information.|author=|date=|work=9news.ph|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, Quiogue suddenly died on May 31, 2013 prior to assuming his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|title=Your life is your message to the world|work=BWorldOnline.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221542/http://www.bworldonline.com/weekender/content.php?id=73221|archivedate=September 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn June 28, 2013, [[Jack City]] reduced its free TV broadcast to 18 hours a day on BEAM in compliance with the [[National Telecommunications Commission]]'s guidelines. However, it still continues to air as a cable channel 24 hours a day.\n\nOn November 9, 2013, [[San Miguel Corporation]]'s president and COO, [[Ramon S. Ang|Ramon Ang]], explored the possibility of acquiring a controlling stake in Solar Entertainment Corporation in his personal capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/13606-san-miguel-s-ang-keen-on-solar-tv,-owner-of-rpn-9|title=San Miguel's Ang keen on Solar TV, owner of RPN-9|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/46828/meeting-of-minds-reached-in-talks-with-ramon-ang-for-investment-says-solar-chairman|title='Meeting of minds' reached in talks with Ramon Ang for investment, says Solar chairman|author=|date=|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> However, no further announcements were made after this and Ang subsequently reached an agreement to acquire a minority stake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|title=EXCLUSIVE - BusinessMirror owner acquires biggest stake in RPN9|work=InterAksyon.com|access-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9|archivedate=August 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Solar News Channel]] and its partnership moved to [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]] on December 1, 2013, while ETC returned to SBN Channel 21 a day before. (ETC was aired on [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN-21]] from 2008 to 2011 then to RPN-9 from 2011 to 2013),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.inquirer.net/177231/new-investor-vows-to-turn-rpn-9-around|title=New investor vows to turn RPN 9 around|first=Miguel R. Camus and Doris C.|last=Dumlao|date=|work=Inquirer.net|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> as well as the launch of Solar's video-on-demand website Blink. As a result of the channel swap (on RPN's part), Network News and Nightly News became newscasts on its own right.\n\nIn 2014, Solar Entertainment's Solar One Boracay happened during the Labor Day weekend to showcase its channels (ETC, 2nd Avenue, JackTV, JackCITY, My Movie Channel, The Game Channel, Solar Sports, BTV and NBA Premium TV) through various summer activities all over the island.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164529/http://www.thedistrictboracay.com/solar-one-boracay-at-the-district-boracay/ |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2014, Solar Entertainment Corporation chief Wilson Tieng announced that he ceded his entire share on [[Solar TV Network]], Inc., including its 34% majority share on RPN, to [[Antonio Cabangon Chua]], owner of business daily [[BusinessMirror]] and [[Aliw Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref>[http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 Exclusive: BusinessMirror owner acquires majority stake in RPN9] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083909/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/93653/exclusive--businessmirror-owner-acquires-majority-stake-in-rpn9 |date=August 22, 2014 }}, InterAksyon.com, August 20, 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2014/08/21/1360003/cabangon-chua-acquires-rpn-9|title=Cabangon-Chua acquires RPN-9|first=Lawrence|last=Agcaoili|date=August 21, 2014|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Tieng sold Solar TV because they were losing money for operations after purchasing RPN. As a result of this ownership change, STVNI, Solar News Channel and RPN's majority stake were separated from the Tiengs; while ETC, 2nd Avenue, and Jack City reverted to Solar Entertainment's ownership.\n\nOn September 1, 2014, [[Jack City]] ended its run on free TV due to the preparations being made by [[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM 31]] for the incoming transition to ISDB-T digital television, though it continues to be broadcast as a separate cable channel. However, Jack City continued to broadcast on cable networks until March 21, 2015. After Jack City's closure to free TV, BEAM aired under blocktime programs from various local production and religious companies. On November 15, 2014, BEAM began being carried on [[SkyCable]] and Destiny Cable subscribers (per compliance with NTC's \"must-carry\" basis). This move resulted of Jack City in a change of its channel assignment for SkyCable and [[Destiny Cable]] subscribers, as well as several pay TV companies.\n\nIn 2015, Solar Entertainment Corporation launched the #1stonPHTV brand of Solar channels for [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]], Jack City and [[My Movie Channel]], with the brand implemented on January 6, 2015. Since then, all SEC channels broadcast first-run foreign television programs with the hashtag #1stonPHTV (First on Philippine TV), which was formerly known as \"Match Airing\" (ETC), \"Playing 1st\" (Jack TV), \"The Newest in the US\" and \"FastCast\" (2nd Avenue) and \"See It First\" (Jack City).\n\n[[The Game Channel]], after almost three years on broadcasting, selling or ceased on February 28, 2015. The channel space was taken over by [[My Movie Channel]] on March 1.\n\nOn March 22, 2015, Jack City was replaced by [[CT (TV channel)|CT]], thus becoming independent from its parent network. Upon launch, the channel broadened its programming focus by adding talk shows, sitcoms and men's lifestyle programs to its roster.\n\nOn March 26, 2015, Solar Entertainment announced its broadcast of the \"Fight Of The Century\" between [[Manny Pacquiao]] and [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] on May 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/sports/2015/03/27/1437964/abs-cbn-gma-tv5-join-hands-air-pacquiao-fight-networks-unite-historic|title=ABS-CBN, GMA, TV5 join hands to air Pacquiao fight: Networks unite for historic broadcast|first=Abac|last=Cordero|date=March 27, 2015|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> As stated in a press conference that day, it was broadcast on May 3 via delayed broadcast in three major television stations in the Philippines, [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]], and [[GMA Network]] (who waived its exclusive contract with Solar to allow its multi-network coverage, but maintained its exclusive live broadcast on its radio division), with [[Solar Sports]] as its main content provider for this historic event in boxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/boxing-mma/pacquiao/88062-pacquiao-mayweather-television-broadcast-ph|title=Pacquiao vs Mayweather to be televised by GMA, ABS-CBN and TV5|author=|date=|work=Rappler.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/459458/sports/boxing/pacquiao-mayweather-fight-to-air-live-over-gma-radio-stations-nationwide|title=Pacquiao-Mayweather fight to air live over GMA radio stations nationwide|author=|date=|work=GMANetwork.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2015, My Movie Channel ceased broadcasting. The closure or selling was announced by Solar a day before.\n\n===Rebranding of the four flagship networks===\nOn October 16, 2016, Solar relaunched its flagship channels ETC, 2nd Avenue, Basketball TV and Solar Sports. The four networks unveiled their new logos, on-air graphics and station IDs, which took effect on that day. CT, Jack TV, Shop TV and NBA Premium TV on the other hand remains unchanged. Also that day, Solar launched its corporate campaign slogan ''...There's More To Come'', which evolved in 2017 as ''We go for More''.\n\nIn 2017, Solar Entertainment became the official Philippine broadcaster of the 65th edition of the [[Miss Universe]] in Manila. This led to another deal with [[ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] and [[GMA Network|GMA]] (the second time that such deal happened between Solar and the Big 3 networks). According to some sources, a directive from [[Rodrigo Duterte|President Duterte]] ordered that the major networks must cover the prestige pageant as it happens live in the [[Philippines]]. Alongside the Big Three, Solar Entertainment channels [[ETC (Philippine TV network)|etc]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Jack TV]] and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] aired the pageant simultaneously. It was also in the same year when Solar Entertainment forged a joint venture with the Bermuda-based communications satellite company [[Asia Broadcast Satellite]] to launch the first nationwide free-to-air [[Satellite television#Direct broadcast via satellite|direct-to-home]] satellite television services using the [[C band (IEEE)|C-band]], which is set to launch on the 3rd quarter of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.satellitetoday.com/broadcasting/2017/05/22/abs-solar-group-launch-new-dth-service-philippines/|title=ABS, The Solar Group to Launch New DTH Service in the Philippines|author=Kendall Russell|date=May 22, 2017|work=Satellite Today|access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Carriage disputes==\n===Sky Cable===\n====2008====\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2014}}\nSolar's channels have ceased airing on [[Sky Cable]], the Philippines' largest cable television provider. An insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that these troubles with Sky Cable started when boxer [[Manny Pacquiao]], whose fights Solar Entertainment has the exclusive right to air and distribute to, moved from [[ABS-CBN]], the flagship television network of [[ABS-CBN Corporation]] and the primary owner of [[Sky Cable Corporation]], to rival [[GMA Network]]. Another insider{{Who|date=April 2017}} claims that SkyCable wanted to remove [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] and [[Jack TV]] to make room for their own channels, [[Velvet (TV channel)|Velvet]] (now defunct) and [[Maxxx]] (now defunct). Sky Cable wanted to retain [[C/S]], [[2nd Avenue (television channel)|2nd Avenue]], [[Solar Sports]] and [[Basketball TV]], but Solar made a decision that they would only renew their contract if Sky Cable carried all six channels. Thus, Solar decided to pull out all their channels rather than remove ETC and Jack TV.\n\nHowever, Solar has signed a deal with local terrestrial channels [[TV5 (Philippines)|ABC]], [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]], [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN]] and [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV]] for block-time programming. C/S, ETC and 2nd Avenue programming are seen on terrestrial TV channels RPN, SBN and RJTV, respectively, while [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] and [[WWE]] programming were seen on TV5, now moved to RPN (WWE programming are currently being broadcast thru TV5, while its terrestrial NBA coverage were moved to [[ABS-CBN Sports]] under Solar).\n\nMost of its channels were later returned to Sky Cable, while Jack TV would eventually return to its lineup on January 1, 2010 replacing Maxxx.\n\nMeanwhile, Pacquiao's boxing promotion, [[Top Rank]], signed a non-guaranteed contract with [[ABS-CBN Sports]] to exclusively air fights promoted by Top Rank, with the exception of Pacquiao fights which are still signed exclusively through Solar Entertainment.\n\n====2017\u201319====\nOn April 10, 2017, 3 days before the [[2017 NBA Playoffs]] was scheduled to begin (and coincided with the final day of the [[2016\u201317 NBA season|2016\u201317 NBA regular season]]), Basketball TV, [[NBA Premium TV]], Solar Sports, Jack TV and [[CT (TV channel)|CT]] (now defunct) were removed by Solar from Sky Cable (including [[Sky Direct]], [[Destiny Cable]] & [[Sky On Demand]] thru video on demand) without any prior announcement from Solar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/basketball/nba/167065-sky-nba-premium-btv-unavailable |title=Sky subscribers frustrated as NBA Premium, BTV unavailable for playoffs start |last= Rola|first=Alyssa |date= April 16, 2017|website=[[Rappler]] |access-date= April 16, 2017|quote=}}</ref> Initially, both Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV were replaced by airing a simulcast of [[ABS-CBN Sports and Action]] with a ticker announcing the unavailability of the channels, with Solar Sports, Jack TV and CT (now defunct) also doing the latter albeit with a black screen. Later, almost all of the pulled-out Solar channels were replaced by an imaging card, initially detailing the unavailability of the channels and then later, announcing that they will discuss with Solar on returning the aforementioned channels; while for BTV and NBA Premium TV, a schedule of the NBA games that will air on [[ABS-CBN]], ABS-CBN Sports and Action and [[Fox Sports Asia|Fox Sports]] within the week and a loop of an NBA promo. Solar did not comment on the situation for the removal of the channels, but sources and some netizens pointed out a carriage dispute between the two parties for not paying an undisclosed price to continue broadcasting these channels, which was later proven true by an article published by the ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]''.\n\nAs the dispute continued, some media enthusiasts and netizens raised concerns of whether these Solar channels will return to Sky and/or Destiny. Others pointed that inaction between the two parties could affect the next long-term local broadcast franchise with the NBA, slated to begin at the Association's 2019-2020 regular season. (Currently, Solar and Sky's parent, ABS-CBN, have a shared broadcast agreement to air the NBA games on pay and terrestrial television, respectively. Rumours circulated that both networks may bid separately, if they could not reach renewal, and use their respective infrastructure to broadcast adequate NBA coverage; otherwise, rival networks with a functioning sports department like [[5 (TV channel)|The 5 Network]] may also seek their own bidding to steal the 2019 contract from both Solar and ABS-CBN.)\n\nNetizens and viewers were dismayed and frustrated by the removal of the said channels by Sky Cable, most notably for BTV and NBA Premium due to the importance of the Playoffs. Some netizens were angered by the removal of the said channels and asked Sky Cable to return the channels before the scheduled Playoffs would begin, however Sky Cable would respond to angered netizens on social media that they are \"fixing the situation with Solar\". Other netizens and viewers would otherwise switch providers from Sky Cable to other cable companies that carried these channels or to other satellite providers like [[Cignal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/news/sky-cable-nba-premium-basketball-tv-negotiations-with-solar |title=SKYcable unable to give timetable for return of NBA Premium, Basketball TV to channel lineup |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=April 15, 2017 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=April 16, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2018, Basketball TV and NBA Premium TV returned to Sky Cable, Sky Direct, & Sky On Demand for the first time in 18 months<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-btv-channels-back-on-skycable-per-advisory-a795-20181016 |title=NBA Premium, BTV channels back on SKYCable, per advisory |last=Terrado |first=Reuben |date=October 16, 2018 |website=[[GMA New Media|Spin.ph]] |access-date=October 26, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>; however it was later removed on October 28, 2018 for unknown reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysky.com.ph/MetroManila/updates/1031/2018/10/28/sky-advisory|title=SKY Advisory|website=Me & My SKY: SKY at 25 years}}</ref>\n\nThe carriage dispute officially ended on January 1, 2019 when all Solar channels: Basketball TV, NBA Premium TV, Solar Sports, and Jack TV were restored on Sky Cable (including Sky On Demand & Sky Direct).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.ph/basketball/nba/nba-premium-and-btv-are-back-in-skycable-s-channel-lineup-a795-20190101|title=NBA Premium and BTV are back in SKYcable's channel lineup|website=Spin.ph}}</ref>\n\nIronically, [[MTVph]], which is a Solar channel, ended its operations on the same day at that time Sky returned the affected Solar channels. As of 2019, Sky Cable's sister company Destiny Cable still does not carry all the aforementioned Solar channels despite its aforementioned return on Sky Cable.\n\nDuring the aforementioned period, [[Shop TV]], ETC and 2nd Avenue (now defunct) were kept on the air, due to the \"must-carry\" rules by the NTC. MTVph was also kept on the air (until it was discontinued on January 1, 2019) since it was carried in a separate programming agreement outside of the affected channels despite its ownership.\n\n===Dream Satellite TV===\n[[Dream Satellite TV]] ceased carrying three Solar Channels, namely [[Solar Sports]], [[ETC (Philippine TV channel)|ETC]] (which was at that time a cable channel prior to its move to free TV and cable) and [[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]] (now defunct) (except [[C/S 9]]) effective 1 February 2009. Dream's carriage contract with Solar Entertainment, which expired on 31 December 2008 was not renewed by Dream, citing financial constraints as its main reason. The three Solar channels were replaced by A&E's [[History (South East Asian TV channel)|The History Channel]], [[Bio. (South East Asia)|Biography Channel]] and [[Crime & Investigation Network (South East Asia)|Crime and Investigation Channel]]. As of 2017, ETC and 2nd Avenue remained on its lineup due to the \"must-carry\" rules of the NTC. \n\nUnfortunately, Dream Satellite ended its operations on December 31, 2017 due to bankruptcy and its competition with other satellite providers.\n\n==Divisions / Subsidiaries==\n* ETC Productions<!-- ETC Productions is a production arm of the female-oriented TV channel, ETC -->\n* Blink\n* Solar Pictures\n* Domestic Satellite Philippines, Inc. (DOMSAT)\n* [[Southern Broadcasting Network]] (acquired in 2010 from Lucio Co's Gem Communications Holdings Corporation)\n* [[Easy TV (Philippines)|Solar Digital Media Holdings]] (operator of Solar's digital television service '''Easy TV Home''')\n\n==Filmography of Solar Pictures==\n===Notable local films released or distributed by Solar Pictures===\n* ''Syota ng Bayan'' (2001)\n* ''[[Batas Militar (2006 film)|Batas Militar]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Pacquiao: The Movie]]'' (2006) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''Anak Ng Kumander'' (2007)\n* ''[[Ang Tanging Pamilya: A Marry Go Round|Ang Tanging Pamilya]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Kimmy Dora: Kambal sa Kiyeme]]'' (2009) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Wapakman]]'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/cebu-entertainment/483549/8-official-entries-2009-mmff-bared|title=8 official entries to 2009 MMFF bared|author=|date=|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Flames of Love'' (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2012/11/05/863321/flames-love-celebrates-year-faith|title=Flames of Love celebrates the Year of Faith|first=Ricky|last=Lo|date=November 5, 2012|work=PhilStar.com|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Sapi'' (2013)\n* ''Mumbai Love'' (2014)\n* ''[[Bonifacio: Ang Unang Pangulo]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Kid Kulafu]]'' (2015) - with [[Star Cinema]]\n* ''[[Ma' Rosa]]'' (2016)\n* ''Mulat'' (2016)\n* ''Apocalypse Child'' (2016)\n* ''[[Ang Larawan]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's Best Picture)\n* ''[[Siargao (film)|Siargao]]'' (2017, 43rd Metro Manila Film Festival's 2nd Best Picture)\n* ''[[Citizen Jake]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Mary, Marry Me]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Rainbow's Sunset]]'' (2018)\n\n==Broadcast assets==\n\n===Terrestrial TV channels===\n* ''[[ETC (Philippine TV network)|ETC]]'' (Cable TV: 2004-present, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2008\u20132011, 2013\u2013present, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2011\u20132013)\n* ''[[Shop TV]]'' (2005\u2013present, digital platform only)\n\n===Cable TV channels===\n* ''Front Row Channel'' (2020-present, joint venture with Jungo TV) \n* ''[[Solar All Access]]'' (2002\u2013present, formerly Solar Sports PPV)\n* ''[[Solar Sports]]'' (1994\u2013present, formerly Solar Entertainment Channel)\n\n===Former subsidiary, divisions and broadcast assets===\n* ''[[Nine Media Corporation]]'' (formerly, Solar Television Network, Inc.; sold to [[Antonio Cabangon-Chua|ALC Group of Companies]])\n** ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (2012\u20132014)\n** ''[[9TV]]'' (2014\u20132015)\n** ''[[Radio Philippines Network]]'' (34%)\n* ''[[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation]]'' (For ''[[NBA]]'', ''[[Shop TV]]'' & ''[[Jai alai|Jai-Alai Games]]'')\n\n===Defunct cable channels and digital TV distribution===\n* ''[[2nd Avenue (TV channel)|2nd Avenue]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132018, [[Rajah Broadcasting Network|RJTV 29]]: 2008\u20132018, formerly ETC 2nd Avenue)\n* ''[[9TV]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2014\u20132015; owned by [[Nine Media Corporation]])\n* ''[[Aniplus Asia]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Basketball TV|BTV]]'' (2006\u20132019)\n* ''[https://whatson.astro.com.my/channels/boo/251/?cat=movies&lang=multiple-language&stb=404 Boo] (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[C/S Origin]]'' (2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[C/S 9]]'' (Cable TV: 2005\u20132007, [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2008\u20132009)\n* ''[[CT (TV channel)|CT]]'' (2015\u20132017)\n* ''[[Chase (TV channel)|Chase]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Diva Universal (Philippines)|Hallmark Channel/Diva Universal Philippines]]'' (2009\u20132013)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Jack City]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2012\u20132014, Cable TV: 2014\u20132015)\n* ''[[Jack TV]]'' (2005\u20132020)\n* ''[[K-Plus (Southeast Asia)|K-Plus]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Living Asia Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[MTV (Southeast Asia)|MTV]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[MTVph]]'' (2017\u20132018, joint venture with [[Viacom International Media Networks Asia]])\n* ''[[My Movie Channel|Blink Cinema/My Movie Channel]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n* ''[[NBA League Pass]]''\n* ''[[NBA Premium TV]]'' (2010\u20132019)\n* ''[[Outdoor Channel]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[Playboy TV]]''\n* ''[[Solar News Channel]]'' (34% joint venture with [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2013\u20132014, [[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2012\u20132013)\n* ''Sports Plus'' (2004\u20132006)\n* ''[[Solar TV]]'' ([[Radio Philippines Network|RPN 9]]: 2009\u20132011)\n* ''[[C/S|Solar USA]]'' (2001\u20132005)\n* ''[[Talk TV (Philippines)|Talk TV]]'' ([[Southern Broadcasting Network|SBN 21]]: 2011\u20132012)\n* ''[[Telenovela Channel]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[The Game Channel|TGC]]'' ([[Broadcast Enterprises and Affiliated Media|BEAM TV 31]]: 2011\u20132012, Cable TV: 2011, 2012\u20132015)\n* ''SciFi/Universal Channel Philippines'' (2009\u20132012)<sup>1</sup>\n* ''[[Zee Sine]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n* ''[[ZooMoo]]'' (2018\u20132019)\n\n{{small|<sup>1</sup>Joint venture with [[Universal Networks International]]}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.solarentertainmentcorp.com}}\n* [http://philippines.mom-rsf.org/en/owners/companies/ Media Ownership Monitor Philippines - Media Companies: A Duopoly Rules] by VERA Files and [[Reporters Without Borders]]\n\n{{Radio Philippines Network}}\n{{Solar Entertainment}}\n{{Television in the Philippines}}\n{{Philippine cable channels}}\n\n[[Category:Solar Entertainment Corporation| ]]\n[[Category:Media companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippine radio networks]]\n[[Category:Philippine television networks]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Television in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2008]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mandaluyong]]\n", "name_user": "LG-Gunther", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_Entertainment_Corporation"}
{"title_page": "Laura Harrier", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Laura Harrier\n| image              = Laura Harrier Cannes 2018 2.jpg\n| caption            = Harrier at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].\n| birth_name         = <!-- Do NOT add unless sourced to a [[WP:RS]] -->\nLaura Ruth Harrier\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1990|3|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[William Esper Studio]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*model\n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2013\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Laura Ruth Harrier'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5637553/|title=Laura Harrier|website=IMDb|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B19ityegF54/|title=LAURA HARRIER\u2019s Instagram post: \u201cbaby laura\u2019s first modeling card \ud83d\udc7c\ud83c\udffd i think i was 14? i was so self conscious because i had recently tripped and fell and my lip got\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> (born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle>{{cite web |author=Chang, Mahalia |date=July 3, 2017 |url=http://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/laura-harrier-spiderman-facts-13641 |title=Everything You Need To Know About \u2018Spider-Man\u2019 Babe, Laura Harrier |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]}}</ref>) is an American actress and former model. Harrier was first recognized for her portrayal of [[Destiny Evans]] in the short-lived reboot of the American [[soap opera]] ''[[One Life to Live]]'' in 2013. In 2017, she made her major film debut portraying [[Liz Allan|Liz]]<!-- Liz's last name is never mentioned in the film nor credits and thus only goes by Liz. However, the character is loosely based on Liz Allan from the comics which is why the comic book character is linked. --><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Laura Harrier confirmed in July 2017 in an interview with ''Total Film'' that the character goes by her mother's maiden name \"Allan\" within the Marvel Cinematic Universe, and that the character would become [[Firestar (comics)|Firestar]] in a future film.</ref> in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anderson, Ethan|date=July 25, 2016|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/spider-man-homecoming-characters/|title=Spider-Man Homecoming Characters Revealed|publisher=[[/Film]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/spider-man-homecoming-casts-laura-harrier-from-one-life-to-live-exclusive/|title='Spider-Man: Homecoming' Casts Laura Harrier From 'One Life to Live' (Exclusive)|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|author=Geier, Thom|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tony-revolori-and-laura-harrier-join-spider-man-homecoming-1201754866/|title=Tony Revolori and Laura Harrier Join 'Spider-Man: Homecoming'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=April 16, 2016|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHarrier was born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle/> in Chicago, Illinois,<ref name=ABCChicago>{{cite web|url=http://abc7chicago.com/entertainment/laura-harrier-star-of-spiderman-homecoming-returns-to-chicago/2127314/|title=Laura Harrier, star of 'Spiderman: Homecoming' returns to Chicago|date=June 21, 2017|publisher=[[WLS-TV]]}}</ref> and was raised in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref name=ABCChicago/> She is biracial with an African-American father and a Caucasian mother.<ref name=TheCut>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/07/laura-harrier-of-spider-man-homecoming-interviewed.html|title=Laughing and Crying With Laura Harrier, the New Star of ''Spider-Man''|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|The Cut]]|author=Weatherford, Ashley|date=July 5, 2017}}</ref> She attended [[Evanston Township High School]] from 2004 to 2008. Her father works in insurance and her mother is a speech pathologist.<ref name=Interview>{{cite web|author=Ortved, John|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/laura-harrier/|title=Laura Harrier|magazine=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> She has one younger brother.<ref name=TheCut/>\n\nHarrier left home for New York at age 18 to attend the [[New York University]] [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]]. Upon arrival, Harrier fell into modeling and deferred enrollment to the university.<ref name=TheCut/> Eventually, she decided that she wanted to pursue acting and attended [[William Esper Studio]] acting school in New York City.<ref name=Interview/><ref name=TheCut/>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nHarrier appeared in the reboot of American soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'' (2013) as Destiny Evans. She has also been in projects such as ''[[The Last Five Years]]'' (2014) and ''[[4th Man Out]]'' (2016).\n\nHarrier had her major film debut playing [[Peter Parker]]'s one-time love interest [[Liz Allan]] in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'' (2017). In June 2017, it was announced that Harrier would be portraying Millie Montag in HBO's film adaptation of acclaimed novel ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]'', opposite [[Michael B. Jordan]];<ref name=\"F451_1\">{{cite web|author=Petski, Denise|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/fahrenheit-451-laura-harrier-cast-millie-hbo-movie-1202120406/amp/|title='Fahrenheit 451': Laura Harrier Cast As Millie In HBO Movie |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=June 2017}}</ref> however, she was later cut from the film.<ref name=\"F451_2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blackkklansman-star-laura-harrier-going-spider-mans-homecoming-cannes-red-carpet/|title=\u2018BlacKkKlansman\u2019 Star Laura Harrier on Going From Spider-Man\u2019s Homecoming to Cannes Red Carpet|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=May 9, 2018|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Harrier co-starred as a civil rights activist in the thriller film ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]'' (2018), opposite [[John David Washington]], [[Adam Driver]], and [[Topher Grace]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=Adam Driver Joins Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Black Klansman\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/adam-driver-spike-lee-black-klansman-1202194537/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=18 May 2018|date=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Harrier starred in ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]'', opposite [[Bria Vinaite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/laura-harrier-bria-vinaite-lily-newmark-board-balance-not-symmetry-with-biffy-clyro-exclusive/5133310.article|title=Laura Harrier, Bria Vinaite, Lily Newmark board 'Balance, Not Symmetry' with Biffy Clyro (exclusive)|website=Screen International|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Modeling and fashion===\nHarrier has modelled for campaigns with companies such as [[Garnier]], [[Urban Outfitters]], [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al]], and has turned up on the pages of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' and ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.\n\nIn 2016, Harrier starred in \"The Realest Real\", a short film for luxury French fashion brand [[Kenzo (brand)|Kenzo]] directed by [[Carrie Brownstein]]. Harrier is currently part of [[Calvin Klein]] and [[Louis Vuitton]] campaigns and is an ambassador for luxury Italian jewelry brand [[Bvlgari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|title=Basel World|publisher=[[Bulgari]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807235801/https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHarrier has been dating American basketball player [[Klay Thompson]] since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/everything-you-should-know-about-nba-star-klay-thompsons-girlfriend-laura-harrier.html/|title=Everything You Should Know About NBA Star Klay Thompson's Girlfriend Laura Harrier|last=Winifred|first=Dirk|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-12-14|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=December 14|first3=2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Denotes films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n===Film and television===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT add \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[One Life to Live]]''\n| [[Destiny Evans]]\n| 43 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Unforgettable''\n| Amber\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Last Five Years (film)|The Last Five Years]]''\n| Manuscript Woman\n| Film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Galyntine''\n| Wylie\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[4th Man Out]]''\n| Dorothy Cuda\n| Film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''\n| [[Liz Allan|Liz]]<!-- Liz's last name is never mentioned in the film nor credits and thus only goes by Liz. However, the character is loosely based on Liz Allan from the comics which is why the comic book character is linked. -->\n| Film\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (2018 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''\n| Millie Montag\n| Television film; deleted scenes<ref name=\"F451_1\" /><ref name=\"F451_2\" />\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]''\n| Patrice\n| Film\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]''\n| Shirley-Caitlin Walker\n| Film\n|-\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Hollywood (American TV series)|Hollywood]]''{{dagger}}\n| Camille Washington\n| Post-production\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Bios (film)|Bios]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The Starling]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|}<!--DO NOT ADD ANYTHING THAT ISN'T PRESENTLY FILMING OR IN POST-PRODUCTION PER [[WP:NFF]] AND 