tripped and fell and my lip got\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> (born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle>{{cite web |author=Chang, Mahalia |date=July 3, 2017 |url=http://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/laura-harrier-spiderman-facts-13641 |title=Everything You Need To Know About \u2018Spider-Man\u2019 Babe, Laura Harrier |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]}}</ref>) is an American actress and former model. Harrier was first recognized for her portrayal of [[Destiny Evans]] in the short-lived reboot of the American [[soap opera]] ''[[One Life to Live]]'' in 2013. In 2017, she made her major film debut portraying [[Liz Allan|Liz]]<!-- Liz's last name is never mentioned in the film nor credits and thus only goes by Liz. However, the character is loosely based on Liz Allan from the comics which is why the comic book character is linked. --><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Laura Harrier confirmed in July 2017 in an interview with ''Total Film'' that the character goes by her mother's maiden name \"Allan\" within the Marvel Cinematic Universe, and that the character would become [[Firestar (comics)|Firestar]] in a future film.</ref> in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anderson, Ethan|date=July 25, 2016|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/spider-man-homecoming-characters/|title=Spider-Man Homecoming Characters Revealed|publisher=[[/Film]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/spider-man-homecoming-casts-laura-harrier-from-one-life-to-live-exclusive/|title='Spider-Man: Homecoming' Casts Laura Harrier From 'One Life to Live' (Exclusive)|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|author=Geier, Thom|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tony-revolori-and-laura-harrier-join-spider-man-homecoming-1201754866/|title=Tony Revolori and Laura Harrier Join 'Spider-Man: Homecoming'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=April 16, 2016|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHarrier was born March 28, 1990<ref name=Elle/> in Chicago, Illinois,<ref name=ABCChicago>{{cite web|url=http://abc7chicago.com/entertainment/laura-harrier-star-of-spiderman-homecoming-returns-to-chicago/2127314/|title=Laura Harrier, star of 'Spiderman: Homecoming' returns to Chicago|date=June 21, 2017|publisher=[[WLS-TV]]}}</ref> and was raised in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref name=ABCChicago/> She is biracial with an African-American father and a Caucasian mother.<ref name=TheCut>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/07/laura-harrier-of-spider-man-homecoming-interviewed.html|title=Laughing and Crying With Laura Harrier, the New Star of ''Spider-Man''|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|The Cut]]|author=Weatherford, Ashley|date=July 5, 2017}}</ref> She attended [[Evanston Township High School]] from 2004 to 2008. Her father works in insurance and her mother is a speech pathologist.<ref name=Interview>{{cite web|author=Ortved, John|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/laura-harrier/|title=Laura Harrier|magazine=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> She has one younger brother.<ref name=TheCut/>\n\nHarrier left home for New York at age 18 to attend the [[New York University]] [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]]. Upon arrival, Harrier fell into modeling and deferred enrollment to the university.<ref name=TheCut/> Eventually, she decided that she wanted to pursue acting and attended [[William Esper Studio]] acting school in New York City.<ref name=Interview/><ref name=TheCut/>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nHarrier appeared in the reboot of American soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'' (2013) as Destiny Evans. She has also been in projects such as ''[[The Last Five Years]]'' (2014) and ''[[4th Man Out]]'' (2016).\n\nHarrier had her major film debut playing [[Peter Parker]]'s one-time love interest [[Liz Allan]] in ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'' (2017). In June 2017, it was announced that Harrier would be portraying Millie Montag in HBO's film adaptation of acclaimed novel ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]'', opposite [[Michael B. Jordan]];<ref name=\"F451_1\">{{cite web|author=Petski, Denise|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/fahrenheit-451-laura-harrier-cast-millie-hbo-movie-1202120406/amp/|title='Fahrenheit 451': Laura Harrier Cast As Millie In HBO Movie |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=June 2017}}</ref> however, she was later cut from the film.<ref name=\"F451_2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blackkklansman-star-laura-harrier-going-spider-mans-homecoming-cannes-red-carpet/|title=\u2018BlacKkKlansman\u2019 Star Laura Harrier on Going From Spider-Man\u2019s Homecoming to Cannes Red Carpet|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=May 9, 2018|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Harrier co-starred as a civil rights activist in the thriller film ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]'' (2018), opposite [[John David Washington]], [[Adam Driver]], and [[Topher Grace]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=Adam Driver Joins Spike Lee\u2019s \u2018Black Klansman\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/adam-driver-spike-lee-black-klansman-1202194537/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=18 May 2018|date=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Harrier starred in ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]'', opposite [[Bria Vinaite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/laura-harrier-bria-vinaite-lily-newmark-board-balance-not-symmetry-with-biffy-clyro-exclusive/5133310.article|title=Laura Harrier, Bria Vinaite, Lily Newmark board 'Balance, Not Symmetry' with Biffy Clyro (exclusive)|website=Screen International|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Modeling and fashion===\nHarrier has modelled for campaigns with companies such as [[Garnier]], [[Urban Outfitters]], [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al]], and has turned up on the pages of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' and ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.\n\nIn 2016, Harrier starred in \"The Realest Real\", a short film for luxury French fashion brand [[Kenzo (brand)|Kenzo]] directed by [[Carrie Brownstein]]. Harrier is currently part of [[Calvin Klein]] and [[Louis Vuitton]] campaigns and is an ambassador for luxury Italian jewelry brand [[Bvlgari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|title=Basel World|publisher=[[Bulgari]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807235801/https://www.bulgari.com/en-us/magazine/jon-kortajarena-the-new-bulgari-global-watches-ambassador|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHarrier has been dating American basketball player [[Klay Thompson]] since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/everything-you-should-know-about-nba-star-klay-thompsons-girlfriend-laura-harrier.html/|title=Everything You Should Know About NBA Star Klay Thompson's Girlfriend Laura Harrier|last=Winifred|first=Dirk|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-12-14|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=December 14|first3=2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Denotes films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n===Film and television===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT add \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=unsortable | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[One Life to Live]]''\n| [[Destiny Evans]]\n| 43 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Unforgettable''\n| Amber\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Last Five Years (film)|The Last Five Years]]''\n| Manuscript Woman\n| Film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Galyntine''\n| Wylie\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[4th Man Out]]''\n| Dorothy Cuda\n| Film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''\n| [[Liz Allan]]\n| Film\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (2018 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''\n| Millie Montag\n| Television film; deleted scenes<ref name=\"F451_1\" /><ref name=\"F451_2\" />\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[BlacKkKlansman]]''\n| Patrice\n| Film\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Balance, Not Symmetry]]''\n| Shirley-Caitlin Walker\n| Film\n|-\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Hollywood (American TV series)|Hollywood]]''{{dagger}}\n| Camille Washington\n| Post-production\n|-\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Bios (film)|Bios]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n| 2020\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The Starling]]''{{dagger}}\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|}<!--DO NOT ADD ANYTHING THAT ISN'T PRESENTLY FILMING OR IN POST-PRODUCTION PER [[WP:NFF]] AND [[WP:CRYSTAL]]-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eckardt, Stephanie (2017 June). \"Laura Harrier Isn't in Spider-Man: Homecoming Just to Look Pretty for Peter Parker\", ''W''. retrieved from https://www.wmagazine.com\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|5637553}}\n* {{Instagram|lauraharrier}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/laura-harrier-louis-vuitton-spiderman-paris-fashion-week-front-row|title=Spiderman\u2019s Laura Harrier Breaks Out in All Black at Louis Vuitton|publisher=}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrier, Laura}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Evanston Township High School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Factfanatic1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Liz's last name is never mentioned in the film nor credits and thus only goes by Liz. However, the character is loosely based on Liz Allan from the comics which is why the comic book character is linked.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Harrier"}
{"title_page": "Jorge Barlin", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = \n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name             =  Jorge Barlin y Imperial \n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            =[[Bishop|First Filipino Bishop in the Catholic Church]]<br>[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caceres|Bishop of Nueva Caceres]]\n| image            = WTNaga EURO B14.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = The Monument of Archbishop Jorge Barlin at Plaza Barlin in [[Naga, Camarines Sur]], [[Philippines]] \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = [[Naga Cathedral|Metropolitan Cathedral of Saint John the Evangelist]] \n| archdiocese      = [[Archdiocese of Caceres]]\n| province         = C\u00e1ceres\n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = Diocese of Nueva C\u00e1ceres\n| see              = [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Nueva C\u00e1ceres]]\n| appointed        = December 14, 1905\n| term             = 1905\u20131909\n| quashed          = September 4, 1909\n| predecessor      = Arsenio del Campo y Monasterio O.E.S.A.\n| successor        = [[John Bernard MacGinley]]\n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = September 19, 1875\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = June 29, 1906\n| consecrated_by   = Archbishop [[Ambrose Agius]], O.S.B.\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1850|04|23}}\n| birth_place      = [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], [[Captaincy General of the Philippines]], [[Spanish Empire]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1909|09|04|1850|04|23}}\n| death_place      = [[Rome]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n| buried           = Cimitero Comunale Monumentale Campo Verano, [[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = Filipino\n| religion         = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| residence        = [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], [[Philippines]]\n| parents          = Mateo Alfonso Barlin (Father)<br>Francisca Imperial (Mother)\n| spouse           = <!-- or | partner = -->\n| children         = \n| occupation       = Archbishop\n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = Signature Jore Barlin.jpg\n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\n\n'''Jorge Barlin''' (April 23, 1850 in [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], [[Philippines]] \u2013 September 4, 1909 in [[Rome]], [[Italy]]) also known as '''Jorge Barlin Imperial''', '''Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin''' and '''Jorge Barlin y Imperial''' following [[Spanish naming customs]], was the first [[Filipino people|Filipino]] consecrated a [[bishop]] in the [[Roman Catholic Church]].  He served as archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caceres]] in the [[Philippines]] until 1909.  He was the first Filipino and [[Bicolano people|Bicolano]] bishop and was parish priest and [[vicar forane]] of [[Sorsogon]] from 1887 to 1906.<ref>page 32, Tracing from Solsogon to Sorsogon, 2nd Edition (2007), {{ISBN|978-971-814-099-4}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nJorge Barlin was born April 23, 1850 in [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], the Philippines to Mateo Alfonso Barlin and Francisca Imperial and died in [[Rome]], [[Italy]] in 1909.<ref name=Findagrave>{{Find a Grave| grid = 59407067|name= Rev Fr Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin||accessdate = March 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was ordained a priest on September 19, 1875 and consecrated a bishop on June 29, 1906 by Archbishop [[Ambrose Agius]] along with co-consecrators Archbishop [[Jeremiah James Harty]] and Bishop [[Frederick Zadok Rooker]].<ref name=\"Findagrave\" />  \"Barlin proved very capable and loyal, dealing a blow to the schismatic Iglesia Filipinia Independiente by resisting its recruitment efforts and winning a court battle over church property,\" according to [[Catholic Bishops Conference of the Philippines]].<ref name=\"PapalVisit2015\">{{cite web|title=The Philippines: \"Arsenal of Faith, Deposit of Christianity in the East\"|url=http://papalvisit.ph/the-church-in-the-philippines/|website=Pope Francis Papal Visit 2015|accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe died and was interred in that holy city.<ref name=\"Findagrave\" /> Attempts to have his body returned to the Philippines were not successful.<ref name=\"Findagrave\" />\n\nThere is a monument commemorating Jorge Barlin called Plaza Barlin in [[Naga, Camarines Sur]] <ref name=\"naga.gov.ph\">{{Cite web|url=http://naga.gov.ph/see-naga/attractions/|title=See what Naga has to offer \u00ab Dagos po sa Maogmang Naga|first=i-Governance|last=Team|accessdate=Oct 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere is another monument of Jorge Barlin in his hometown's plaza, Baao, Camarines Sur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nhcphistoricsites.blogspot.com/2011/10/jorge-barlin-national-monument.html|title=National Registry of Historic Sites and Structures in the Philippines|last=|first=|date=|website=National Registry of Historic Sites and Structures in the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Catholic Church in the Philippines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Alarcon, R.A. (2009). ''The Episcopal Consecration of Bishop Jorge Barlin: A New Phase in Philippine Church History''. Philippiniana Sacra XLIV(131).\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|59407067|Rev Fr Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box \n|    title=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caceres|Bishop of Nueva Caceres]] \n|    before= [[Arsenio del Campo y Monasterio]]\n|    after=[[John Bernard MacGinley]]\n|    years=1905\u20131909}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Philippines}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barlin, Jorge}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:People from Camarines Sur]]\n[[Category:19th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:People from Baao, Camarines Sur]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = \n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name             =  Jorge Barlin y Imperial \n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            =[[Bishop|First Filipino Bishop in the Catholic Church]]<br>[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caceres|Bishop of Nueva Caceres]]\n| image            = WTNaga EURO B14.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = The Monument of Archbishop Jorge Barlin at Plaza Barlin in [[Naga, Camarines Sur]], [[Philippines]] \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = [[Naga Cathedral|Metropolitan Cathedral of Saint John the Evangelist]] \n| archdiocese      = [[Archdiocese of Caceres]]\n| province         = C\u00e1ceres\n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = Diocese of Nueva C\u00e1ceres\n| see              = [[Naga|Nueva C\u00e1ceres]]\n| appointed        = December 14, 1905\n| term             = 1905\u20131909\n| quashed          = September 4, 1909\n| predecessor      = Arsenio del Campo y Monasterio O.E.S.A.\n| successor        = [[John Bernard MacGinley]]\n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = September 19, 1875\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = June 29, 1906\n| consecrated_by   = Archbishop [[Ambrose Agius]], O.S.B.\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1850|04|23}}\n| birth_place      = [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], [[Captaincy General of the Philippines]], [[Spanish Empire]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1909|09|04|1850|04|23}}\n| death_place      = [[Rome]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n| buried           = Cimitero Comunale Monumentale Campo Verano, [[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = Filipino\n| religion         = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| residence        = [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], [[Philippines]]\n| parents          = Mateo Alfonso Barlin (Father)<br>Francisca Imperial (Mother)\n| spouse           = <!-- or | partner = -->\n| children         = \n| occupation       = Archbishop\n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = Signature Jore Barlin.jpg\n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\n\n'''Jorge Barlin''' (April 23, 1850 in [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], [[Philippines]] \u2013 September 4, 1909 in [[Rome]], [[Italy]]) also known as '''Jorge Barlin Imperial''', '''Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin''' and '''Jorge Barlin y Imperial''' following [[Spanish naming customs]], was the first [[Filipino people|Filipino]] consecrated a [[bishop]] in the [[Roman Catholic Church]].  He served as archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caceres]] in the [[Philippines]] until 1909.  He was the first Filipino and [[Bicolano people|Bicolano]] bishop and was parish priest and [[vicar forane]] of [[Sorsogon]] from 1887 to 1906.<ref>page 32, Tracing from Solsogon to Sorsogon, 2nd Edition (2007), {{ISBN|978-971-814-099-4}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nJorge Barlin was born April 23, 1850 in [[Baao, Camarines Sur]], the Philippines to Mateo Alfonso Barlin and Francisca Imperial and died in [[Rome]], [[Italy]] in 1909.<ref name=Findagrave>{{Find a Grave| grid = 59407067|name= Rev Fr Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin||accessdate = March 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was ordained a priest on September 19, 1875 and consecrated a bishop on June 29, 1906 by Archbishop [[Ambrose Agius]] along with co-consecrators Archbishop [[Jeremiah James Harty]] and Bishop [[Frederick Zadok Rooker]].<ref name=\"Findagrave\" />  \"Barlin proved very capable and loyal, dealing a blow to the schismatic Iglesia Filipinia Independiente by resisting its recruitment efforts and winning a court battle over church property,\" according to [[Catholic Bishops Conference of the Philippines]].<ref name=\"PapalVisit2015\">{{cite web|title=The Philippines: \"Arsenal of Faith, Deposit of Christianity in the East\"|url=http://papalvisit.ph/the-church-in-the-philippines/|website=Pope Francis Papal Visit 2015|accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe died and was interred in that holy city.<ref name=\"Findagrave\" /> Attempts to have his body returned to the Philippines were not successful.<ref name=\"Findagrave\" />\n\nThere is a monument commemorating Jorge Barlin called Plaza Barlin in [[Naga, Camarines Sur]] <ref name=\"naga.gov.ph\">{{Cite web|url=http://naga.gov.ph/see-naga/attractions/|title=See what Naga has to offer \u00ab Dagos po sa Maogmang Naga|first=i-Governance|last=Team|accessdate=Oct 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere is another monument of Jorge Barlin in his hometown's plaza, Baao, Camarines Sur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nhcphistoricsites.blogspot.com/2011/10/jorge-barlin-national-monument.html|title=National Registry of Historic Sites and Structures in the Philippines|last=|first=|date=|website=National Registry of Historic Sites and Structures in the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Catholic Church in the Philippines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Alarcon, R.A. (2009). ''The Episcopal Consecration of Bishop Jorge Barlin: A New Phase in Philippine Church History''. Philippiniana Sacra XLIV(131).\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|59407067|Rev Fr Jorge Alfonso Imperial Barlin}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box \n|    title=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Caceres|Bishop of Nueva Caceres]] \n|    before= [[Arsenio del Campo y Monasterio]]\n|    after=[[John Bernard MacGinley]]\n|    years=1905\u20131909}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Philippines}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barlin, Jorge}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:People from Camarines Sur]]\n[[Category:19th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:People from Baao, Camarines Sur]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguate link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorge_Barlin"}
{"title_page": "L\u00e9o Taxil", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:L\u00e9o Taxil (Melandri).jpg|thumb|L\u00e9o Taxil]]\n'''Marie Joseph Gabriel Antoine Jogand-Pag\u00e8s''', better known by the [[pen name]] '''L\u00e9o Taxil''' ({{IPA-fr|leo taksil|lang}}; March 21, 1854 &ndash; March 31, 1907), was a [[France|French]] writer and journalist who became known for his strong anti-Catholic and anti-clerical views. He is also known for the [[Taxil hoax]], a spurious expos\u00e9 of [[Freemasonry]] and the [[Roman Catholic Church]]'s opposition to it.\n\n==Early life==\nMarie Joseph Gabriel Antoine Jogand-Pag\u00e8s was born in [[Marseille]], and at the age of five, he was placed into a [[Jesuit]] seminary. After spending his childhood years in the seminary, he became disillusioned with the Catholic faith and began to see the religious ideology as socially harmful.\n\n==La Bible amusante==\nTaxil first became known for writing [[Anti-clericalism|anti-Clerical]] or [[anti-Catholic]] books,<ref>Robin Waterfield, Rene Guenon and the Future of the West, Published, 1987, p.32-36 {{ISBN|1597310190}}</ref> notably ''[[La Bible amusante]]'' (''The Amusing Bible'') and ''La Vie de Jesus'' (''The Life of Jesus''), in which Taxil satirically pointed out inconsistencies, errors, and false beliefs presented in these religious works. In his other books ''Les D\u00e9bauches d'un confesseur'' (''Debauchery of a Confessor'', with Karl Milo), ''Les Pornographes sacr\u00e9s: la confession et les confesseurs'' (''Sacred Pornographs: confession and confessors''), and ''Les Ma\u00eetresses du Pape'' (''The Pope's Mistresses''), Taxil portrays leaders of the Catholic Church as hedonistic creatures exploring their fetishes in the manner of the [[Marquis de Sade]]. In 1879, he was tried at the Seine [[Cour d'assises|Assizes]] for writing a pamphlet ''A Bas la Calotte'' (\"Down with the Cloth\"), which was accused of insulting a religion recognized by the state, but he was acquitted.\n\n==The Taxil hoax==\n{{main|Taxil hoax}}\nIn 1885, he professed conversion to Catholicism, was solemnly received into the church, and renounced his earlier works. In the 1890s, he wrote a series of pamphlets and books denouncing [[Freemasonry]],<ref name=HC>[[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]], ''Mysteries of the Freemasons: America'', video documentary, August 1, 2006, written by Noah Nicholas and Molly Bedell</ref> charging their lodges with worshiping the devil and alleging that Diana Vaughan had written for him her confessions of the Satanic \"[[Palladist]]\" cult. The book had great sales among Catholics, although Diana Vaughan never appeared in public. In 1892, Taxil also began to publish a paper, ''La France chr\u00e9tienne anti-ma\u00e7onnique (Christian Antimasonic France)'', with his staunch anti-Masonic publishing friend, [[Abel Clarin de la Rive]].<ref name=IIT>Is It True What They Say About Freemasonry? Authors: de Hoyos, Arturo and Morris, S. Brent, 1988, 2nd edition, p. 27-36, Leo Taxil: The Hoax of Luciferian Masonry {{ISBN|1590771532}}</ref> In 1887, he had an audience with [[Pope Leo XIII]], who rebuked the [[Diocese of Charleston|bishop of Charleston]] for denouncing the [[Anti-Masonry|anti-Masonic]] confessions as a fraud and, in 1896, sent his blessing to an anti-Masonic Congress of [[Trento|Trent]].<ref>Story of Freemasonry \n by W. G. Sibley, p. 35, Kessinger Publishing, LLC (April 1, 1996), {{ISBN|1564598225}}</ref>\n\nDoubts about Vaughan's veracity and even her existence began to grow, and finally, Taxil promised to produce her at a lecture to be delivered by him on 19 April 1897. To the amazement of the audience (which included a number of [[priest]]s), he announced that Diana was one of a series of hoaxes.<ref name=HC/><ref name=IIT/> He had begun, he said, by persuading the commandant of Marseille that the harbor was infested with sharks, and a ship was sent to destroy them. Next, he invented an underwater city in [[Lake Geneva]], drawing tourists and archaeologists to the spot. He thanked the bishops and Catholic newspapers for facilitating his crowning hoax, namely his conversion, which had exposed the anti-Masonic fanaticism of many Catholics. Diana Vaughan was revealed to be a simple typist in his employ, who laughingly allowed her name to be used by him.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n\nThe audience received these revelations with indignation and contempt. Afterwards, Taxil left the hall, where policemen escorted him to a neighboring caf\u00e9. He then moved away from Paris. He died in [[Sceaux, Hauts-de-Seine|Sceaux]] in 1907 of unknown reason.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n\n==Selected Books==\n*''La Vie de J\u00e9sus (The Life of Jesus)'' (1900)\n*''[[La Bible amusante]] (The Amusing Bible)'' (1882)\n*''Les D\u00e9bauches d'un confesseur (The Debaucheries of a Confessor)'' (1884, with Karl Milo)\n*''Les Pornographes sacr\u00e9s: la confession et les confesseurs (The Holy Pornographers: Confession and Confessors)'' (1882)\n*''Les Ma\u00eetresses du Pape (The Pope's Mistresses)'' (1884)\n*''Le Martyre de Jeanne d'Arc'' ''(The Martyrdom of [[Joan of Arc]])'' (1890, with Paul Fesch; edition of Pierre Cauchon's manuscripts of Joan of Arc's trial)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=JO-CJZ-cOz8C&pg=PA1010&lpg=PA1010&dq=%22pierre+Cauchon%22+Pope+Callixtus+III&source=bl&ots=Km6mp0bvNH&sig=RW2TpF5z-HyVYjYzZsZmnCYWC5I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf947UuJ3RAhUnwVQKHRX4CLEQ6AEIPTAI#v=onepage&q=%22pierre%20Cauchon%22%20Pope%20Callixtus%20III&f=false \"Reviews: ''Le Martyre de J\u00e9anne d'Arc''] by L\u00e9o Taxil\" ''[[The Tablet]]'', Vol. 75 No. 2616 (June 28, 1890), pps. 1010-1011 [[Google Books]] December 30, 2016</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[The Prague Cemetery]]'', [[novel]] by [[Umberto Eco]], 2010\n* [[Abel Clarin de la Rive|Wikipedia article on Abel Clarin de la Rive and the Luciferian texts.]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Satan Franc-Ma\u00e7on: la mystification de L\u00e9o Taxil'', 1964.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|L\u00e9o Taxil}}\n*[http://www.sacred-texts.com/evil/dwf/index.htm A.E. Waite, ''Devil-Worship in France''] complete e-text of Waite's 1896 debunking of Taxil.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taxil, Leo}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1907 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Marseille]]\n[[Category:Anti-Masonry]]\n[[Category:French atheists]]\n[[Category:Anti-Catholicism in France]]\n[[Category:Former Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Critics of the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:L\u00e9o Taxil (Melandri).jpg|thumb|L\u00e9o Taxil]]\n'''Marie Joseph Gabriel Antoine Jogand-Pag\u00e8s''', better known by the [[pen name]] '''L\u00e9o Taxil''' ({{IPA-fr|leo taksil|lang}}; March 21, 1854 &ndash; March 31, 1907), was a [[France|French]] writer and journalist who became known for his strong anti-Catholic and anti-clerical views. He is also known for the [[Taxil hoax]], a spurious expos\u00e9 of [[Freemasonry]] and the [[Roman Catholic Church]]'s opposition to it.\n\n==Early life==\nMarie Joseph Gabriel Antoine Jogand-Pag\u00e8s was born in [[Marseille]], and at the age of five, he was placed into a [[Jesuit]] seminary. After spending his childhood years in the seminary, he became disillusioned with the Catholic faith and began to see the religious ideology as socially harmful.\n\n==La Bible amusante==\nTaxil first became known for writing [[Anti-clericalism|anti-Clerical]] or [[anti-Catholic]] books,<ref>Robin Waterfield, Rene Guenon and the Future of the West, Published, 1987, p.32-36 {{ISBN|1597310190}}</ref> notably ''[[La Bible amusante]]'' (''The Amusing Bible'') and ''La Vie de Jesus'' (''The Life of Jesus''), in which Taxil satirically pointed out inconsistencies, errors, and false beliefs presented in these religious works. In his other books ''Les D\u00e9bauches d'un confesseur'' (''Debauchery of a Confessor'', with Karl Milo), ''Les Pornographes sacr\u00e9s: la confession et les confesseurs'' (''Sacred Pornographs: confession and confessors''), and ''Les Ma\u00eetresses du Pape'' (''The Pope's Mistresses''), Taxil portrays leaders of the Catholic Church as hedonistic creatures exploring their fetishes in the manner of the [[Marquis de Sade]]. In 1879, he was tried at the Seine [[Cour d'assises|Assizes]] for writing a pamphlet ''A Bas la Calotte'' (\"Down with the Cloth\"), which was accused of insulting a religion recognized by the state, but he was acquitted.\n\n==The Taxil hoax==\n{{main|Taxil hoax}}\nIn 1885, he professed conversion to Catholicism, was solemnly received into the church, and renounced his earlier works. In the 1890s, he wrote a series of pamphlets and books denouncing [[Freemasonry]],<ref name=HC>[[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]], ''Mysteries of the Freemasons: America'', video documentary, August 1, 2006, written by Noah Nicholas and Molly Bedell</ref> charging their lodges with worshiping the devil and alleging that Diana Vaughan had written for him her confessions of the Satanic \"[[Palladist]]\" cult. The book had great sales among Catholics, although Diana Vaughan never appeared in public. In 1892, Taxil also began to publish a paper, ''La France chr\u00e9tienne anti-ma\u00e7onnique (Christian Antimasonic France)'', with his staunch anti-Masonic publishing friend, [[Abel Clarin de la Rive]].<ref name=IIT>Is It True What They Say About Freemasonry? Authors: de Hoyos, Arturo and Morris, S. Brent, 1988, 2nd edition, p. 27-36, Leo Taxil: The Hoax of Luciferian Masonry {{ISBN|1590771532}}</ref> In 1887, he had an audience with [[Pope Leo XIII]], who rebuked the [[Diocese of Charleston|bishop of Charleston]] for denouncing the [[Anti-Masonry|anti-Masonic]] confessions as a fraud and, in 1896, sent his blessing to an anti-Masonic Congress of [[Trento|Trent]].<ref>Story of Freemasonry \n by W. G. Sibley, p. 35, Kessinger Publishing, LLC (April 1, 1996), {{ISBN|1564598225}}</ref>\n\nDoubts about Vaughan's veracity and even her existence began to grow, and finally, Taxil promised to produce her at a lecture to be delivered by him on 19 April 1897. To the amazement of the audience (which included a number of [[priest]]s), he announced that Diana was one of a series of hoaxes.<ref name=HC/><ref name=IIT/> He had begun, he said, by persuading the commandant of Marseille that the harbor was infested with sharks, and a ship was sent to destroy them. Next, he invented an underwater city in [[Lake Geneva]], drawing tourists and archaeologists to the spot. He thanked the bishops and Catholic newspapers for facilitating his crowning hoax, namely his conversion, which had exposed the anti-Masonic fanaticism of many Catholics. Diana Vaughan was revealed to be a simple typist in his employ, who laughingly allowed her name to be used by him.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n\nThe audience received these revelations with indignation and contempt. Afterwards, Taxil left the hall, where policemen escorted him to a neighboring caf\u00e9. He then moved away from Paris. He died in [[Sceaux, Hauts-de-Seine|Sceaux]] in 1907.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n\n==Selected Books==\n*''La Vie de J\u00e9sus (The Life of Jesus)'' (1900)\n*''[[La Bible amusante]] (The Amusing Bible)'' (1882)\n*''Les D\u00e9bauches d'un confesseur (The Debaucheries of a Confessor)'' (1884, with Karl Milo)\n*''Les Pornographes sacr\u00e9s: la confession et les confesseurs (The Holy Pornographers: Confession and Confessors)'' (1882)\n*''Les Ma\u00eetresses du Pape (The Pope's Mistresses)'' (1884)\n*''Le Martyre de Jeanne d'Arc'' ''(The Martyrdom of [[Joan of Arc]])'' (1890, with Paul Fesch; edition of Pierre Cauchon's manuscripts of Joan of Arc's trial)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=JO-CJZ-cOz8C&pg=PA1010&lpg=PA1010&dq=%22pierre+Cauchon%22+Pope+Callixtus+III&source=bl&ots=Km6mp0bvNH&sig=RW2TpF5z-HyVYjYzZsZmnCYWC5I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf947UuJ3RAhUnwVQKHRX4CLEQ6AEIPTAI#v=onepage&q=%22pierre%20Cauchon%22%20Pope%20Callixtus%20III&f=false \"Reviews: ''Le Martyre de J\u00e9anne d'Arc''] by L\u00e9o Taxil\" ''[[The Tablet]]'', Vol. 75 No. 2616 (June 28, 1890), pps. 1010-1011 [[Google Books]] December 30, 2016</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[The Prague Cemetery]]'', [[novel]] by [[Umberto Eco]], 2010\n* [[Abel Clarin de la Rive|Wikipedia article on Abel Clarin de la Rive and the Luciferian texts.]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Satan Franc-Ma\u00e7on: la mystification de L\u00e9o Taxil'', 1964.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|L\u00e9o Taxil}}\n*[http://www.sacred-texts.com/evil/dwf/index.htm A.E. Waite, ''Devil-Worship in France''] complete e-text of Waite's 1896 debunking of Taxil.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taxil, Leo}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1907 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Marseille]]\n[[Category:Anti-Masonry]]\n[[Category:French atheists]]\n[[Category:Anti-Catholicism in France]]\n[[Category:Former Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Critics of the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Lovemankind83", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%C3%A9o_Taxil"}
{"title_page": "Bristol Manor Farm F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = The Farm, Farmy Army, The Portwaymen \n| ground = The Creek, [[Bristol]]\n| capacity = 2,000 (200 seated)\n| season = {{English football updater|BristoMF2}}\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b1 = _black_chest\n| pattern_b2 = _black_chest\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_so1 = _redtop\n| pattern_so2 = _blacktop\n| leftarm1 = 000000\n| leftarm2 = 000000\n| body1 = FF0000\n| body2 = FFFF00\n| rightarm1 = 000000\n| rightarm2 = 000000\n| shorts1 = 000000\n| shorts2 = FFFF00\n| socks1 = 000000\n| socks2 = FFFF00\n| clubname = \n| fullname = Bristol Manor Farm Football Club\n| image = Bristol Manor Farm badge NEW PNG.png\n| image_size = 201px\n| founded = 1960\n| chairman = Geoff Sellek\n| manager = Lee Lashenko\n| league = {{English football updater|BristoMF}}\n| position = {{English football updater|BristoMF3}}\n}}\n\n'''Bristol Manor Farm Football Club''' is an [[England|English]] [[Association football|football club]] based in [[Bristol]], [[England]]. They are currently members of the {{English football updater|BristoMF}} and play at The Creek. The club is affiliated to the [[Gloucestershire County FA]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Creek, Bristol Manor Farm.jpg|alt=|thumb|400x400px|Bristol Manor Farm's ground, The Creek, in 2015]]\nBristol Manor Farm Football Club was formed for the 1960/61 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bristolmanorfarm.com/history.php|title=Club History|publisher=Bristol Manor Farm FC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708094805/http://www.bristolmanorfarm.com/history.php|archive-date=2011-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> After just one season, the club was disbanded but was reformed and began playing again in the 1962/63 season. Their current home The Creek used to be the site of the Port of Bristol Authority Sports & Social Club but when they moved to new premises 1965, Manor Farm took it over. The pitch at the Creek was once notorious for its sloping surface but work has been undertaken in recent years to eliminate the slope. With seating and floodlights added since 1980, the club now boasts excellent facilities alongside a spacious clubhouse.\n \nHaving a permanent base enabled the club to apply successfully to join the Somerset Senior League where they were to progress rapidly through the divisions before deciding to advance further to the Western League in 1977.\n \nThe club joined the First Division for the 1977/78 season and remained there until the 1982/83 season when they won the First Division championship and gained promotion to the Premier Division. They remained there until relegation under Pete McCall's management team in 2001/02 but regained their Premier status just two seasons later in 2003/04 under Shaun Bond and Nicky Johns. In 1983/84 they reached the final of the G.F.A. Challenge Trophy where they lost to then Hellenic League side [[Shortwood United]]. The trophy did make its way to the Creek in 1987/88 and has been won on a further three occasions by the club.\n \n \nMain stand at The Creek.\nThe 2011/12 season saw the club win its first double when they took both the GFA Challenge Trophy and the Toolstation League Les Phillips League Cup back to Sea Mills.\n \nLee Lashenko become the new manager at the start of the 2013/14 season and quickly made an impact in the [[FA Cup]], overcoming [[Oldland Abbotonians F.C.|Oldland Abootonians]], [[Lymington Town F.C.|Lymington Town]] and [[Corsham Town]] to reach the Second Qualifying Round, equaling their best ever performance in the competition. Unfortunately, they were unable to go one better and lost to [[Bridgwater Town]] 1-2 in a replay at Fairfax Park. The club continued to fight for top spot in the league and applied for promotion. The club finished second but were unsuccessful in their promotion bid when [[Larkhall Athletic F.C.|Larkhall Athletic]] were accepted into the Southern League. The second-placed finish was the best in the club's history. It also saw the team break the club records for the most goals scored in a season and the fewest goals conceded.\n \nThe 2015/16 season left the club with mixed feelings as on one hand they managed to get to the Quarter-Final of the [[FA Vase]] narrowly going out away to eventual winners [[Morpeth Town]]. On the other hand, whilst they finished 3rd in the Western League, again they just missed out on promotion to the Southern League by one place. They did, however, win the GFA County Challenge Trophy for the second time in succession and the fourth time overall with a record 9-2 win over [[Lydney Town F.C.|Lydney Town]].\n \nIn the 2016/17 season, Bristol Manor Farm were finally successful in gaining promotion to the Southern League, winning the Western League by quite a distance. They also had another successful run in the FA Vase where they went out in the Fifth Round Proper to Semi-Finalists [[Bromsgrove Sporting F.C.|Bromsgrove Sporting]].\n \nThe Farm finished their first season in the eighth tier with a very respectable 9th-place finish, falling away towards the end after troubling the top six places all season.\n\n== Staff ==\n \n*'''First team manager''': Lee Lashenko\n*'''Assistant manager''': Iain Harvey\n*'''Physio''': Stephen Carter\n*'''Coach(s)''': Chris Bailes, Terry Buffrey, [[Mike Mahoney (footballer)|Mike Mahoney]]\n\n== Club rivals ==\nBristol Manor Farm's main rivals are considered to be [[Yate Town F.C.|Yate Town]] and [[Mangotsfield United F.C.|Mangotsfield United]], both from the northern outskirts of Bristol. With all three clubs playing in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League Division One]] since 2017, fixtures among the three have been seen by some fans as a contest to claim the title of Bristol's third club and tend to attract higher than usual attendances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mufc-online.co.uk/teams/32267/match-centre/1-2862155|title=Bristol Manor Farm 3 vs. 1 Mangotsfield United - 16 September 2017 - First Team - Mangotsfield United FC \u2122|website=www.mufc-online.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/yatetownfootballclub/teams/97151/match-centre/1-2862485|title=Bristol Manor Farm 1 vs. 1 Yate Town - 24 March 2018 - 1st Team - Yate Town Football Club|website=www.pitchero.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[Western Football League]] Premier Division'''<ref name=\"FCHD\">{{Fchd|id=BRISTOMF|name=Bristol Manor Farm}}</ref>\n**Champions: [[2016\u201317 Western Football League#Premier Division|2016-17]]\n**Runners-up: [[2013\u201314 Western Football League#Premier Division|2013-14]]\n*'''[[Western Football League]] Division One'''<ref name=\"FCHD\">{{Fchd|id=BRISTOMF|name=Bristol Manor Farm}}</ref>\n**Champions: [[1982\u201383 Western Football League#First Division|1982\u201383]]\n\n==Cup Honours==\n*'''Gloucestershire Football Association Challenge Trophy'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gloucestershirefa.com/|title=The website for Gloucestershire FA|first=The Football|last=Association|date=|website=www.gloucestershirefa.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n** Winners: 1987-88, 2011\u201312, 2014\u201315, 2015-16<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gloucestershirefa.com/cups/2015-2016/challenge-trophy/results#final|title=Cups & Competitions|first=The Football|last=Association|date=|website=www.gloucestershirefa.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Western Football League]] Cup''':<ref>{{cite web|title=Les Phillips Cup Winners|url=http://www.toolstationleague.com/history2.php|publisher=Toolstation Western League|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n** Winners: 2011-12\n\n==Seasons==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Season\n!Division\n!Pos\n!P\n!W\n!D\n!L\n!F\n!A\n!GD\n!Pts\n!FA Cup\n!FA Trophy\n!FA Vase\n|-\n|[[1977\u201378 Western Football League|1977\u201378]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Division 1]]\n|4th\n|36\n|20\n|5\n|11\n|67\n|38\n| +29\n|65\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[1978\u201379 Western Football League|1978\u201379]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Division 1]]\n|3rd\n|36\n|20\n|5\n|11\n|59\n|47\n| +12\n|65\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n| PR\n|-\n|[[1979\u201380 Western Football League|1979\u201380]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Division 1]]\n|8th\n|42\n|20\n|9\n|13\n|70\n|58\n| +12\n|49\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n| R1\n|-\n|[[1980\u201381 Western Football League|1980\u201381]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Division 1]]\n|10th\n|36\n|14\n|8\n|14\n|53\n|57\n| \u20134\n|36\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n| R1\n|-\n|[[1981\u201382 Western Football League|1981\u201382]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Division 1]]\n|8th\n|36\n|15\n|9\n|12\n|58\n|50\n| +8\n|39\n| \u2013\n| \u2013\n| R1\n|-\n|[[1982\u201383 Western Football League|1982\u201383]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Division 1]]\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|1st\n|36\n|26\n|7\n|3\n|85\n|31\n| +54\n|59\n| QR2\n| \u2013\n| R3\n|-\n|[[1983\u201384 Western Football League|1983\u201384]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Premier Division]]\n|8th\n|38\n|14\n|11\n|13\n|54\n|42\n| +12\n|39\n| PR\n| \u2013\n| R5\n|-\n|[[1984\u201385 Western Football League|1984\u201385]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Premier Division]]\n|6th\n|42\n|21\n|7\n|14\n|70\n|55\n| +15\n|49\n| PR\n| \u2013\n| R4\n|-\n|[[1985\u201386 Western Football League|1985\u201386]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Premier Division]]\n|11th\n|42\n|16\n|9\n|17\n|71\n|72\n| \u20131\n|41\n| QR1\n| PR\n| \u2013\n|-\n|[[1986\u201387 Western Football League|1986\u201387]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western Football League Premier Division]]\n|5th\n|42\n|19\n|10\n|13\n|58\n|46\n| +12\n|48\n| PR\n| \u2013\n| R1\n|-\n|[[1987\u201388 Western Football League|1987\u201388]]\n|[[Western Football League|Western 